\
\'93It could not be worse,\'94 Passini said respectfully. \'93There is nothing\
worse than war.\'94\
\
\'93Defeat is worse.\'94\
\
\'93I do not believe it,\'94 Passini said still respectfully. \'93What is defeat?\
You go home.\'94\
\
\'93They come after you. They take your home. They take your sisters.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t believe it,\'94 Passini said. \'93They can\'92t do that to everybody.\
Let everybody defend his home. Let them keep their sisters in the\
house.\'94\
\
\'93They hang you. They come and make you be a soldier again. Not in the\
auto-ambulance, in the infantry.\'94\
\
\'93They can\'92t hang every one.\'94\
\
\'93An outside nation can\'92t make you be a soldier,\'94 Manera said. \'93At the\
first battle you all run.\'94\
\
\'93Like the Tchecos.\'94\
\
\'93I think you do not know anything about being conquered and so you think\
it is not bad.\'94\
\
\'93Tenente,\'94 Passini said. \'93We understand you let us talk. Listen. There\
is nothing as bad as war. We in the auto-ambulance cannot even realize\
at all how bad it is. When people realize how bad it is they cannot do\
anything to stop it because they go crazy. There are some people who\
never realize. There are people who are afraid of their officers. It is\
with them that war is made.\'94\
\
\'93I know it is bad but we must finish it.\'94\
\
\'93It doesn\'92t finish. There is no finish to a war.\'94\
\
\'93Yes there is.\'94\
\
Passini shook his head.\
\
\'93War is not won by victory. What if we take San Gabriele? What if we\
take the Carso and Monfalcone and Trieste? Where are we then? Did you\
see all the far mountains to-day? Do you think we could take all them\
too? Only if the Austrians stop fighting. One side must stop fighting.\
Why don\'92t we stop fighting? If they come down into Italy they will get\
tired and go away. They have their own country. But no, instead there is\
a war.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re an orator.\'94\
\
\'93We think. We read. We are not peasants. We are mechanics. But even the\
peasants know better than to believe in a war. Everybody hates this\
war.\'94\
\
\'93There is a class that controls a country that is stupid and does not\
realize anything and never can. That is why we have this war.\'94\
\
\'93Also they make money out of it.\'94\
\
\'93Most of them don\'92t,\'94 said Passini. \'93They are too stupid. They do it for\
nothing. For stupidity.\'94\
\
\'93We must shut up,\'94 said Manera. \'93We talk too much even for the Tenente.\'94\
\
\'93He likes it,\'94 said Passini. \'93We will convert him.\'94\
\
\'93But now we will shut up,\'94 Manera said.\
\
\'93Do we eat yet, Tenente?\'94 Gavuzzi asked.\
\
\'93I will go and see,\'94 I said. Gordini stood up and went outside with me.\
\
\'93Is there anything I can do, Tenente? Can I help in any way?\'94 He was the\
quietest one of the four. \'93Come with me if you want,\'94 I said, \'93and we\'92ll\
see.\'94\
\
It was dark outside and the long light from the search-lights was moving\
over the mountains. There were big search-lights on that front mounted\
on camions that you passed sometimes on the roads at night, close behind\
the lines, the camion stopped a little off the road, an officer\
directing the light and the crew scared. We crossed the brickyard, and\
stopped at the main dressing station. There was a little shelter of\
green branches outside over the entrance and in the dark the night wind\
rustled the leaves dried by the sun. Inside there was a light. The major\
was at the telephone sitting on a box. One of the medical captains said\
the attack had been put forward an hour. He offered me a glass of\
cognac. I looked at the board tables, the instruments shining in the\
light, the basins and the stoppered bottles. Gordini stood behind me.\
The major got up from the telephone.\
\
\'93It starts now,\'94 he said. \'93It has been put back again.\'94\
\
I looked outside, it was dark and the Austrian search-lights were moving\
on the mountains behind us. It was quiet for a moment still, then from\
all the guns behind us the bombardment started.\
\
\'93Savoia,\'94 said the major.\
\
\'93About the soup, major,\'94 I said. He did not hear me. I repeated it.\
\
\'93It hasn\'92t come up.\'94\
\
A big shell came in and burst outside in the brickyard. Another burst\
and in the noise you could hear the smaller noise of the brick and dirt\
raining down.\
\
\'93What is there to eat?\'94\
\
\'93We have a little pasta asciutta,\'94 the major said.\
\
\'93I\'92ll take what you can give me.\'94\
\
The major spoke to an orderly who went out of sight in the back and came\
back with a metal basin of cold cooked macaroni. I handed it to Gordini.\
\
\'93Have you any cheese?\'94\
\
The major spoke grudgingly to the orderly who ducked back into the hole\
again and came out with a quarter of a white cheese.\
\
\'93Thank you very much,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93You\'92d better not go out.\'94\
\
Outside something was set down beside the entrance. One of the two men\
who had carried it looked in.\
\
\'93Bring him in,\'94 said the major. \'93What\'92s the matter with you? Do you want\
us to come outside and get him?\'94\
\
The two stretcher-bearers picked up the man under the arms and by the\
legs and brought him in.\
\
\'93Slit the tunic,\'94 the major said.\
\
He held a forceps with some gauze in the end. The two captains took off\
their coats. \'93Get out of here,\'94 the major said to the two\
stretcher-bearers.\
\
\'93Come on,\'94 I said to Gordini.\
\
\'93You better wait until the shelling is over,\'94 the major said over his\
shoulder.\
\
\'93They want to eat,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93As you wish.\'94\
\
Outside we ran across the brickyard. A shell burst short near the river\
bank. Then there was one that we did not hear coming until the sudden\
rush. We both went flat and with the flash and bump of the burst and the\
smell heard the singing off of the fragments and the rattle of falling\
brick. Gordini got up and ran for the dugout. I was after him, holding\
the cheese, its smooth surface covered with brick dust. Inside the\
dugout were the three drivers sitting against the wall, smoking.\
\
\'93Here, you patriots,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93How are the cars?\'94 Manera asked.\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Did they scare you, Tenente?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re damned right,\'94 I said.\
\
I took out my knife, opened it, wiped off the blade and pared off the\
dirty outside surface of the cheese. Gavuzzi handed me the basin of\
macaroni.\
\
\'93Start in to eat, Tenente.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93Put it on the floor. We\'92ll all eat.\'94\
\
\'93There are no forks.\'94\
\
\'93What the hell,\'94 I said in English.\
\
I cut the cheese into pieces and laid them on the macaroni.\
\
\'93Sit down to it,\'94 I said. They sat down and waited. I put thumb and\
fingers into the macaroni and lifted. A mass loosened.\
\
\'93Lift it high, Tenente.\'94\
\
I lifted it to arm\'92s length and the strands cleared. I lowered it into\
the mouth, sucked and snapped in the ends, and chewed, then took a bite\
of cheese, chewed, and then a drink of the wine. It tasted of rusty\
metal. I handed the canteen back to Passini.\
\
\'93It\'92s rotten,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s been in there too long. I had it in the\
car.\'94\
\
They were all eating, holding their chins close over the basin, tipping\
their heads back, sucking in the ends. I took another mouthful and some\
cheese and a rinse of wine. Something landed outside that shook the\
earth.\
\
\'93Four hundred twenty or minnenwerfer,\'94 Gavuzzi said.\
\
\'93There aren\'92t any four hundred twenties in the mountains,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93They have big Skoda guns. I\'92ve seen the holes.\'94\
\
\'93Three hundred fives.\'94\
\
We went on eating. There was a cough, a noise like a railway engine\
starting and then an explosion that shook the earth again.\
\
\'93This isn\'92t a deep dugout,\'94 Passini said.\
\
\'93That was a big trench-mortar.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, sir.\'94\
\
I ate the end of my piece of cheese and took a swallow of wine. Through\
the other noise I heard a cough, then came the chuh-chuh-chuh-chuh\'97then\
there was a flash, as when a blast-furnace door is swung open, and a\
roar that started white and went red and on and on in a rushing wind. I\
tried to breathe but my breath would not come and I felt myself rush\
bodily out of myself and out and out and out and all the time bodily in\
the wind. I went out swiftly, all of myself, and I knew I was dead and\
that it had all been a mistake to think you just died. Then I floated,\
and instead of going on I felt myself slide back. I breathed and I was\
back. The ground was torn up and in front of my head there was a\
splintered beam of wood. In the jolt of my head I heard somebody crying.\
I thought somebody was screaming. I tried to move but I could not move.\
I heard the machine-guns and rifles firing across the river and all\
along the river. There was a great splashing and I saw the star-shells\
go up and burst and float whitely and rockets going up and heard the\
bombs, all this in a moment, and then I heard close to me some one\
saying \'93Mama Mia! Oh, mama Mia!\'94 I pulled and twisted and got my legs\
loose finally and turned around and touched him. It was Passini and when\
I touched him he screamed. His legs were toward me and I saw in the dark\
and the light that they were both smashed above the knee. One leg was\
gone and the other was held by tendons and part of the trouser and the\
stump twitched and jerked as though it were not connected. He bit his\
arm and moaned, \'93Oh mama mia, mama Mia,\'94 then, \'93Dio te salve, Maria. Dio\
te salve, Maria. Oh Jesus shoot me Christ shoot me mama mia mama Mia oh\
purest lovely Mary shoot me. Stop it. Stop it. Stop it. Oh Jesus lovely\
Mary stop it. Oh oh oh oh,\'94 then choking, \'93Mama mama mia.\'94 Then he was\
quiet, biting his arm, the stump of his leg twitching.\
\
\'93Porta feriti!\'94 I shouted holding my hands cupped. \'93Porta Feriti!\'94 I\
tried to get closer to Passini to try to put a tourniquet on the legs\
but I could not move. I tried again and my legs moved a little. I could\
pull backward along with my arms and elbows. Passini was quiet now. I\
sat beside him, undid my tunic and tried to rip the tail of my shirt. It\
would not rip and I bit the edge of the cloth to start it. Then I\
thought of his puttees. I had on wool stockings but Passini wore\
puttees. All the drivers wore puttees but Passini had only one leg. I\
unwound the puttee and while I was doing it I saw there was no need to\
try and make a tourniquet because he was dead already. I made sure he\
was dead. There were three others to locate. I sat up straight and as I\
did so something inside my head moved like the weights on a doll\'92s eyes\
and it hit me inside in back of my eyeballs. My legs felt warm and wet\
and my shoes were wet and warm inside. I knew that I was hit and leaned\
over and put my hand on my knee. My knee wasn\'92t there. My hand went in\
and my knee was down on my shin. I wiped my hand on my shirt and another\
floating light came very slowly down and I looked at my leg and was very\
afraid. Oh, God, I said, get me out of here. I knew, however, that there\
had been three others. There were four drivers. Passini was dead. That\
left three. Some one took hold of me under the arms and somebody else\
lifted my legs.\
\
\'93There are three others,\'94 I said. \'93One is dead.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s Manera. We went for a stretcher but there wasn\'92t any. How are you,\
Tenente?\'94\
\
\'93Where is Gordini and Gavuzzi?\'94\
\
\'93Gordini\'92s at the post getting bandaged. Gavuzzi has your legs. Hold on\
to my neck, Tenente. Are you badly hit?\'94\
\
\'93In the leg. How is Gordini?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s all right. It was a big trench-mortar shell.\'94\
\
\'93Passini\'92s dead.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. He\'92s dead.\'94\
\
A shell fell close and they both dropped to the ground and dropped me.\
\'93I\'92m sorry, Tenente,\'94 said Manera. \'93Hang onto my neck.\'94\
\
\'93If you drop me again.\'94\
\
\'93It was because we were scared.\'94\
\
\'93Are you unwounded?\'94\
\
\'93We are both wounded a little.\'94\
\
\'93Can Gordini drive?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think so.\'94\
\
They dropped me once more before we reached the post.\
\
\'93You sons of bitches,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I am sorry, Tenente,\'94 Manera said. \'93We won\'92t drop you again.\'94\
\
Outside the post a great many of us lay on the ground in the dark. They\
carried wounded in and brought them out. I could see the light come out\
from the dressing station when the curtain opened and they brought some\
one in or out. The dead were off to one side. The doctors were working\
with their sleeves up to their shoulders and were red as butchers. There\
were not enough stretchers. Some of the wounded were noisy but most were\
quiet. The wind blew the leaves in the bower over the door of the\
dressing station and the night was getting cold. Stretcher-bearers came\
in all the time, put their stretchers down, unloaded them and went away.\
As soon as I got to the dressing station Manera brought a medical\
sergeant out and he put bandages on both my legs. He said there was so\
much dirt blown into the wound that there had not been much hemorrhage.\
They would take me as soon as possible. He went back inside. Gordini\
could not drive, Manera said. His shoulder was smashed and his head was\
hurt. He had not felt bad but now the shoulder had stiffened. He was\
sitting up beside one of the brick walls. Manera and Gavuzzi each went\
off with a load of wounded. They could drive all right. The British had\
come with three ambulances and they had two men on each ambulance. One\
of their drivers came over to me, brought by Gordini who looked very\
white and sick. The Britisher leaned over.\
\
\'93Are you hit badly?\'94 he asked. He was a tall man and wore steel-rimmed\
spectacles.\
\
\'93In the legs.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s not serious I hope. Will you have a cigarette?\'94\
\
\'93Thanks.\'94\
\
\'93They tell me you\'92ve lost two drivers.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. One killed and the fellow that brought you.\'94\
\
\'93What rotten luck. Would you like us to take the cars?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s what I wanted to ask you.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92d take quite good care of them and return them to the Villa. 206\
aren\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a charming place. I\'92ve seen you about. They tell me you\'92re an\
American.\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m English.\'94\
\
\'93No!\'94\
\
\'93Yes, English. Did you think I was Italian? There were some Italians\
with one of our units.\'94\
\
\'93It would be fine if you would take the cars,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We\'92ll be most careful of them,\'94 he straightened up. \'93This chap of yours\
was very anxious for me to see you.\'94 He patted Gordini on the shoulder.\
Gordini winced and smiled. The Englishman broke into voluble and perfect\
Italian. \'93Now everything is arranged. I\'92ve seen your Tenente. We will\
take over the two cars. You won\'92t worry now.\'94 He broke off, \'93I must do\
something about getting you out of here. I\'92ll see the medical wallahs.\
We\'92ll take you back with us.\'94\
\
He walked across to the dressing station, stepping carefully among the\
wounded. I saw the blanket open, the light came out and he went in.\
\
\'93He will look after you, Tenente,\'94 Gordini said.\
\
\'93How are you, Franco?\'94\
\
\'93I am all right.\'94 He sat down beside me. In a moment the blanket in\
front of the dressing station opened and two stretcher-bearers came out\
followed by the tall Englishman. He brought them over to me.\
\
\'93Here is the American Tenente,\'94 he said in Italian.\
\
\'93I\'92d rather wait,\'94 I said. \'93There are much worse wounded than me. I\'92m\
all right.\'94\
\
\'93Come come,\'94 he said. \'93Don\'92t be a bloody hero.\'94 Then in Italian: \'93Lift\
him very carefully about the legs. His legs are very painful. He is the\
legitimate son of President Wilson.\'94 They picked me up and took me into\
the dressing room. Inside they were operating on all the tables. The\
little major looked at us furious. He recognized me and waved a forceps.\
\
\'93\'c7a va bien?\'94\
\
\'93\'c7a va.\'94\
\
\'93I have brought him in,\'94 the tall Englishman said in Italian. \'93The only\
son of the American Ambassador. He can be here until you are ready to\
take him. Then I will take him with my first load.\'94 He bent over me.\
\'93I\'92ll look up their adjutant to do your papers and it will all go much\
faster.\'94 He stooped to go under the doorway and went out. The major was\
unhooking the forceps now, dropping them in a basin. I followed his\
hands with my eyes. Now he was bandaging. Then the stretcher-bearers\
took the man off the table.\
\
\'93I\'92ll take the American Tenente,\'94 one of the captains said. They lifted\
me onto the table. It was hard and slippery. There were many strong\
smells, chemical smells and the sweet smell of blood. They took off my\
trousers and the medical captain commenced dictating to the\
sergeant-adjutant while he worked, \'93Multiple superficial wounds of the\
left and right thigh and left and right knee and right foot. Profound\
wounds of right knee and foot. Lacerations of the scalp (he probed\'97Does\
that hurt?\'97Christ, yes!) with possible fracture of the skull. Incurred\
in the line of duty. That\'92s what keeps you from being court-martialled\
for self-inflicted wounds,\'94 he said. \'93Would you like a drink of brandy?\
How did you run into this thing anyway? What were you trying to do?\
Commit suicide? Anti-tetanus please, and mark a cross on both legs.\
Thank you. I\'92ll clean this up a little, wash it out, and put on a\
dressing. Your blood coagulates beautifully.\'94\
\
The adjutant, looking up from the paper, \'93What inflicted the wounds?\'94\
\
The medical captain, \'93What hit you?\'94\
\
Me, with the eyes shut, \'93A trench mortar shell.\'94\
\
The captain, doing things that hurt sharply and severing tissue\'97\'93Are\
you sure?\'94\
\
Me\'97trying to lie still and feeling my stomach flutter when the flesh\
was cut, \'93I think so.\'94\
\
Captain doctor\'97(interested in something he was finding), \'93Fragments of\
enemy trench-mortar shell. Now I\'92ll probe for some of this if you like\
but it\'92s not necessary. I\'92ll paint all this and\'97Does that sting? Good,\
that\'92s nothing to how it will feel later. The pain hasn\'92t started yet.\
Bring him a glass of brandy. The shock dulls the pain; but this is all\
right, you have nothing to worry about if it doesn\'92t infect and it\
rarely does now. How is your head?\'94\
\
\'93Good Christ!\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Better not drink too much brandy then. If you\'92ve got a fracture you\
don\'92t want inflammation. How does that feel?\'94\
\
Sweat ran all over me.\
\
\'93Good Christ!\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I guess you\'92ve got a fracture all right. I\'92ll wrap you up and don\'92t\
bounce your head around.\'94 He bandaged, his hands moving very fast and\
the bandage coming taut and sure. \'93All right, good luck and Vive la\
France.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s an American,\'94 one of the other captains said.\
\
\'93I thought you said he was a Frenchman. He talks French,\'94 the captain\
said. \'93I\'92ve known him before. I always thought he was French.\'94 He drank\
a half tumbler of cognac. \'93Bring on something serious. Get some more of\
that Anti-tetanus.\'94 The captain waved to me. They lifted me and the\
blanket-flap went across my face as we went out. Outside the\
sergeant-adjutant knelt down beside me where I lay, \'93Name?\'94 he asked\
softly. \'93Middle name? First name? Rank? Where born? What class? What\
corps?\'94 and so on. \'93I\'92m sorry for your head, Tenente. I hope you feel\
better. I\'92m sending you now with the English ambulance.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m all right,\'94 I said. \'93Thank you very much.\'94 The pain that the major\
had spoken about had started and all that was happening was without\
interest or relation. After a while the English ambulance came up and\
they put me onto a stretcher and lifted the stretcher up to the\
ambulance level and shoved it in. There was another stretcher by the\
side with a man on it whose nose I could see, waxy-looking, out of the\
bandages. He breathed very heavily. There were stretchers lifted and\
slid into the slings above. The tall English driver came around and\
looked in, \'93I\'92ll take it very easily,\'94 he said. \'93I hope you\'92ll be\
comfy.\'94 I felt the engine start, felt him climb up into the front seat,\
felt the brake come off and the clutch go in, then we started. I lay\
still and let the pain ride.\
\
As the ambulance climbed along the road, it was slow in the traffic,\
sometimes it stopped, sometimes it backed on a turn, then finally it\
climbed quite fast. I felt something dripping. At first it dropped\
slowly and regularly, then it pattered into a stream. I shouted to the\
driver. He stopped the car and looked in through the hole behind his\
seat.\
\
\'93What is it?\'94\
\
\'93The man on the stretcher over me has a hemorrhage.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92re not far from the top. I wouldn\'92t be able to get the stretcher out\
alone.\'94 He started the car. The stream kept on. In the dark I could not\
see where it came from the canvas overhead. I tried to move sideways so\
that it did not fall on me. Where it had run down under my shirt it was\
warm and sticky. I was cold and my leg hurt so that it made me sick.\
After a while the stream from the stretcher above lessened and started\
to drip again and I heard and felt the canvas above move as the man on\
the stretcher settled more comfortably.\
\
\'93How is he?\'94 the Englishman called back. \'93We\'92re almost up.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s dead I think,\'94 I said.\
\
The drops fell very slowly, as they fall from an icicle after the sun\
has gone. It was cold in the car in the night as the road climbed. At\
the post on the top they took the stretcher out and put another in and\
we went on.\
\
\
\
\
                               CHAPTER X\
\
In the ward at the field hospital they told me a visitor was coming to\
see me in the afternoon. It was a hot day and there were many flies in\
the room. My orderly had cut paper into strips and tied the strips to a\
stick to make a brush that swished the flies away. I watched them settle\
on the ceiling. When he stopped swishing and fell asleep they came down\
and I blew them away and finally covered my face with my hands and slept\
too. It was very hot and when I woke my legs itched. I waked the orderly\
and he poured mineral water on the dressings. That made the bed damp and\
cool. Those of us that were awake talked across the ward. The afternoon\
was a quiet time. In the morning they came to each bed in turn, three\
men nurses and a doctor and picked you up out of bed and carried you\
into the dressing room so that the beds could be made while we were\
having our wounds dressed. It was not a pleasant trip to the dressing\
room and I did not know until later that beds could be made with men in\
them. My orderly had finished pouring water and the bed felt cool and\
lovely and I was telling him where to scratch on the soles of my feet\
against the itching when one of the doctors brought in Rinaldi. He came\
in very fast and bent down over the bed and kissed me. I saw he wore\
gloves.\
\
\'93How are you, baby? How do you feel? I bring you this\'97\'94 It was a bottle\
of cognac. The orderly brought a chair and he sat down, \'93and good news.\
You will be decorated. They want to get you the medaglia d\'92argento but\
perhaps they can get only the bronze.\'94\
\
\'93What for?\'94\
\
\'93Because you are gravely wounded. They say if you can prove you did any\
heroic act you can get the silver. Otherwise it will be the bronze. Tell\
me exactly what happened. Did you do any heroic act?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I was blown up while we were eating cheese.\'94\
\
\'93Be serious. You must have done something heroic either before or after.\
Remember carefully.\'94\
\
\'93I did not.\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t you carry anybody on your back? Gordini says you carried several\
people on your back but the medical major at the first post declares it\
is impossible. He has to sign the proposition for the citation.\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t carry anybody. I couldn\'92t move.\'94\
\
\'93That doesn\'92t matter,\'94 said Rinaldi.\
\
He took off his gloves.\
\
\'93I think we can get you the silver. Didn\'92t you refuse to be medically\
aided before the others?\'94\
\
\'93Not very firmly.\'94\
\
\'93That doesn\'92t matter. Look how you are wounded. Look at your valorous\
conduct in asking to go always to the first line. Besides, the operation\
was successful.\'94\
\
\'93Did they cross the river all right?\'94\
\
\'93Enormously. They take nearly a thousand prisoners. It\'92s in the\
bulletin. Didn\'92t you see it?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll bring it to you. It is a successful coup de main.\'94\
\
\'93How is everything?\'94\
\
\'93Splendid. We are all splendid. Everybody is proud of you. Tell me just\
exactly how it happened. I am positive you will get the silver. Go on\
tell me. Tell me all about it.\'94 He paused and thought. \'93Maybe you will\
get an English medal too. There was an English there. I\'92ll go and see\
him and ask if he will recommend you. He ought to be able to do\
something. Do you suffer much? Have a drink. Orderly, go get a\
corkscrew. Oh you should see what I did in the removal of three metres\
of small intestine and better now than ever. It is one for _The Lancet_.\
You do me a translation and I will send it to _The Lancet_. Every day I\
am better. Poor dear baby, how do you feel? Where is that damn\
corkscrew? You are so brave and quiet I forget you are suffering.\'94 He\
slapped his gloves on the edge of the bed.\
\
\'93Here is the corkscrew, Signor Tenente,\'94 the orderly said.\
\
\'93Open the bottle. Bring a glass. Drink that, baby. How is your poor\
head? I looked at your papers. You haven\'92t any fracture. That major at\
the first post was a hog-butcher. I would take you and never hurt you. I\
never hurt anybody. I learn how to do it. Every day I learn to do things\
smoother and better. You must forgive me for talking so much, baby. I am\
very moved to see you badly wounded. There, drink that. It\'92s good. It\
cost fifteen lire. It ought to be good. Five stars. After I leave here\
I\'92ll go see that English and he\'92ll get you an English medal.\'94\
\
\'93They don\'92t give them like that.\'94\
\
\'93You are so modest. I will send the liaison officer. He can handle the\
English.\'94\
\
\'93Have you seen Miss Barkley?\'94\
\
\'93I will bring her here. I will go now and bring her here.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t go,\'94 I said. \'93Tell me about Gorizia. How are the girls?\'94\
\
\'93There are no girls. For two weeks now they haven\'92t changed them. I\
don\'92t go there any more. It is disgraceful. They aren\'92t girls; they are\
old war comrades.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t go at all?\'94\
\
\'93I just go to see if there is anything new. I stop by. They all ask for\
you. It is a disgrace that they should stay so long that they become\
friends.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe girls don\'92t want to go to the front any more.\'94\
\
\'93Of course they do. They have plenty of girls. It is just bad\
administration. They are keeping them for the pleasure of dugout hiders\
in the rear.\'94\
\
\'93Poor Rinaldi,\'94 I said. \'93All alone at the war with no new girls.\'94\
\
Rinaldi poured himself another glass of the cognac.\
\
\'93I don\'92t think it will hurt you, baby. You take it.\'94\
\
I drank the cognac and felt it warm all the way down. Rinaldi poured\
another glass. He was quieter now. He held up the glass. \'93To your\
valorous wounds. To the silver medal. Tell me, baby, when you lie here\
all the time in the hot weather don\'92t you get excited?\'94\
\
\'93Sometimes.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t imagine lying like that. I would go crazy.\'94\
\
\'93You are crazy.\'94\
\
\'93I wish you were back. No one to come in at night from adventures. No\
one to make fun of. No one to lend me money. No blood brother and\
roommate. Why do you get yourself wounded?\'94\
\
\'93You can make fun of the priest.\'94\
\
\'93That priest. It isn\'92t me that makes fun of him. It is the captain. I\
like him. If you must have a priest have that priest. He\'92s coming to see\
you. He makes big preparations.\'94\
\
\'93I like him.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I knew it. Sometimes I think you and he are a little that way. You\
know.\'94\
\
\'93No, you don\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I do sometimes. A little that way like the number of the first\
regiment of the Brigata Ancona.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, go to hell.\'94\
\
He stood up and put on his gloves.\
\
\'93Oh I love to tease you, baby. With your priest and your English girl,\
and really you are just like me underneath.\'94\
\
\'93No, I\'92m not.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, we are. You are really an Italian. All fire and smoke and nothing\
inside. You only pretend to be American. We are brothers and we love\
each other.\'94\
\
\'93Be good while I\'92m gone,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I will send Miss Barkley. You are better with her without me. You are\
purer and sweeter.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, go to hell.\'94\
\
\'93I will send her. Your lovely cool goddess. English goddess. My God what\
would a man do with a woman like that except worship her? What else is\
an Englishwoman good for?\'94\
\
\'93You are an ignorant foul-mouthed dago.\'94\
\
\'93A what?\'94\
\
\'93An ignorant wop.\'94\
\
\'93Wop. You are a frozen-faced ... wop.\'94\
\
\'93You are ignorant. Stupid.\'94 I saw that word pricked him and kept on.\
\'93Uninformed. Inexperienced, stupid from inexperience.\'94\
\
\'93Truly? I tell you something about your good women. Your goddesses.\
There is only one difference between taking a girl who has always been\
good and a woman. With a girl it is painful. That\'92s all I know.\'94 He\
slapped the bed with his glove. \'93And you never know if the girl will\
really like it.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t get angry.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not angry. I just tell you, baby, for your own good. To save you\
trouble.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the only difference?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. But millions of fools like you don\'92t know it.\'94\
\
\'93You were sweet to tell me.\'94\
\
\'93We won\'92t quarrel, baby. I love you too much. But don\'92t be a fool.\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92ll be wise like you.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be angry, baby. Laugh. Take a drink. I must go, really.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re a good old boy.\'94\
\
\'93Now you see. Underneath we are the same. We are war brothers. Kiss me\
good-by.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re sloppy.\'94\
\
\'93No. I am just more affectionate.\'94\
\
I felt his breath come toward me. \'93Good-by. I come to see you again\
soon.\'94 His breath went away. \'93I won\'92t kiss you if you don\'92t want. I\'92ll\
send your English girl. Good-by, baby. The cognac is under the bed. Get\
well soon.\'94\
\
He was gone.\
