\
\
\
\
                              CHAPTER XIII\
\
We got into Milan early in the morning and they unloaded us in the\
freight yard. An ambulance took me to the American hospital. Riding in\
the ambulance on a stretcher I could not tell what part of town we were\
passing through but when they unloaded the stretcher I saw a\
market-place and an open wine shop with a girl sweeping out. They were\
watering the street and it smelled of the early morning. They put the\
stretcher down and went in. The porter came out with them. He had gray\
mustaches, wore a doorman\'92s cap and was in his shirt sleeves. The\
stretcher would not go into the elevator and they discussed whether it\
was better to lift me off the stretcher and go up in the elevator or\
carry the stretcher up the stairs. I listened to them discussing it.\
They decided on the elevator. They lifted me from the stretcher. \'93Go\
easy,\'94 I said. \'93Take it softly.\'94\
\
In the elevator we were crowded and as my legs bent the pain was very\
bad. \'93Straighten out the legs,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We can\'92t, Signor Tenente. There isn\'92t room.\'94 The man who said this had\
his arm around me and my arm was around his neck. His breath came in my\
face metallic with garlic and red wine.\
\
\'93Be gentle,\'94 the other man said.\
\
\'93Son of a bitch who isn\'92t gentle!\'94\
\
\'93Be gentle I say,\'94 the man with my feet repeated.\
\
I saw the doors of the elevator closed, and the grill shut and the\
fourth-floor button pushed by the porter. The porter looked worried. The\
elevator rose slowly.\
\
\'93Heavy?\'94 I asked the man with the garlic.\
\
\'93Nothing,\'94 he said. His face was sweating and he grunted. The elevator\
rose steadily and stopped. The man holding the feet opened the door and\
stepped out. We were on a balcony. There were several doors with brass\
knobs. The man carrying the feet pushed a button that rang a bell. We\
heard it inside the doors. No one came. Then the porter came up the\
stairs.\
\
\'93Where are they?\'94 the stretcher-bearers asked.\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 said the porter. \'93They sleep down stairs.\'94\
\
\'93Get somebody.\'94\
\
The porter rang the bell, then knocked on the door, then he opened the\
door and went in. When he came back there was an elderly woman wearing\
glasses with him. Her hair was loose and half-falling and she wore a\
nurse\'92s dress.\
\
\'93I can\'92t understand,\'94 she said. \'93I can\'92t understand Italian.\'94\
\
\'93I can speak English,\'94 I said. \'93They want to put me somewhere.\'94\
\
\'93None of the rooms are ready. There isn\'92t any patient expected.\'94 She\
tucked at her hair and looked at me near-sightedly.\
\
\'93Show them any room where they can put me.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 she said. \'93There\'92s no patient expected. I couldn\'92t put\
you in just any room.\'94\
\
\'93Any room will do,\'94 I said. Then to the porter in Italian, \'93Find an\
empty room.\'94\
\
\'93They are all empty,\'94 said the porter. \'93You are the first patient.\'94 He\
held his cap in his hand and looked at the elderly nurse.\
\
\'93For Christ\'92s sweet sake take me to some room.\'94 The pain had gone on and\
on with the legs bent and I could feel it going in and out of the bone.\
The porter went in the door, followed by the gray-haired woman, then\
came hurrying back. \'93Follow me,\'94 he said. They carried me down a long\
hallway and into a room with drawn blinds. It smelled of new furniture.\
There was a bed and a big wardrobe with a mirror. They laid me down on\
the bed.\
\
\'93I can\'92t put on sheets,\'94 the woman said. \'93The sheets are locked up.\'94\
\
I did not speak to her. \'93There is money in my pocket,\'94 I said to the\
porter. \'93In the buttoned-down pocket.\'94 The porter took out the money.\
The two stretcher-bearers stood beside the bed holding their caps. \'93Give\
them five lire apiece and five lire for yourself. My papers are in the\
other pocket. You may give them to the nurse.\'94\
\
The stretcher-bearers saluted and said thank you. \'93Good-by,\'94 I said.\
\'93And many thanks.\'94 They saluted again and went out.\
\
\'93Those papers,\'94 I said to the nurse, \'93describe my case and the treatment\
already given.\'94\
\
The woman picked them up and looked at them through her glasses. There\
were three papers and they were folded. \'93I don\'92t know what to do,\'94 she\
said. \'93I can\'92t read Italian. I can\'92t do anything without the doctor\'92s\
orders.\'94 She commenced to cry and put the papers in her apron pocket.\
\'93Are you an American?\'94 she asked crying.\
\
\'93Yes. Please put the papers on the table by the bed.\'94\
\
It was dim and cool in the room. As I lay on the bed I could see the big\
mirror on the other side of the room but could not see what it\
reflected. The porter stood by the bed. He had a nice face and was very\
kind.\
\
\'93You can go,\'94 I said to him. \'93You can go too,\'94 I said to the nurse.\
\'93What is your name?\'94\
\
\'93Mrs. Walker.\'94\
\
\'93You can go, Mrs. Walker. I think I will go to sleep.\'94\
\
I was alone in the room. It was cool and did not smell like a hospital.\
The mattress was firm and comfortable and I lay without moving, hardly\
breathing, happy in feeling the pain lessen. After a while I wanted a\
drink of water and found the bell on a cord by the bed and rang it but\
nobody came. I went to sleep.\
\
When I woke I looked around. There was sunlight coming in through the\
shutters. I saw the big armoire, the bare walls, and two chairs. My legs\
in the dirty bandages, stuck straight out in the bed. I was careful not\
to move them. I was thirsty and I reached for the bell and pushed the\
button. I heard the door open and looked and it was a nurse. She looked\
young and pretty.\
\
\'93Good-morning,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Good-morning,\'94 she said and came over to the bed. \'93We haven\'92t been able\
to get the doctor. He\'92s gone to Lake Como. No one knew there was a\
patient coming. What\'92s wrong with you anyway?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m wounded. In the legs and feet and my head is hurt.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s your name?\'94\
\
\'93Henry. Frederic Henry.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll wash you up. But we can\'92t do anything to the dressings until the\
doctor comes.\'94\
\
\'93Is Miss Barkley here?\'94\
\
\'93No. There\'92s no one by that name here.\'94\
\
\'93Who was the woman who cried when I came in?\'94\
\
The nurse laughed. \'93That\'92s Mrs. Walker. She was on night duty and she\'92d\
been asleep. She wasn\'92t expecting any one.\'94\
\
While we were talking she was undressing me, and when I was undressed,\
except for the bandages, she washed me, very gently and smoothly. The\
washing felt very good. There was a bandage on my head but she washed\
all around the edge.\
\
\'93Where were you wounded?\'94\
\
\'93On the Isonzo north of Plava.\'94\
\
\'93Where is that?\'94\
\
\'93North of Gorizia.\'94\
\
I could see that none of the places meant anything to her.\
\
\'93Do you have a lot of pain?\'94\
\
\'93No. Not much now.\'94\
\
She put a thermometer in my mouth.\
\
\'93The Italians put it under the arm,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t talk.\'94\
\
When she took the thermometer out she read it and then shook it.\
\
\'93What\'92s the temperature?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re not supposed to know that.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me what it is.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s almost normal.\'94\
\
\'93I never have any fever. My legs are full of old iron too.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re full of trench-mortar fragments, old screws and bed-springs and\
things.\'94\
\
She shook her head and smiled.\
\
\'93If you had any foreign bodies in your legs they would set up an\
inflammation and you\'92d have fever.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93We\'92ll see what comes out.\'94\
\
She went out of the room and came back with the old nurse of the early\
morning. Together they made the bed with me in it. That was new to me\
and an admirable proceeding.\
\
\'93Who is in charge here?\'94\
\
\'93Miss Van Campen.\'94\
\
\'93How many nurses are there?\'94\
\
\'93Just us two.\'94\
\
\'93Won\'92t there be more?\'94\
\
\'93Some more are coming.\'94\
\
\'93When will they get here?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. You ask a great many questions for a sick boy.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not sick,\'94 I said, \'93I\'92m wounded.\'94\
\
They had finished making the bed and I lay with a clean smooth sheet\
under me and another sheet over me. Mrs. Walker went out and came back\
with a pajama jacket. They put that on me and I felt very clean and\
dressed.\
\
\'93You\'92re awfully nice to me,\'94 I said. The nurse called Miss Gage giggled.\
\'93Could I have a drink of water?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Certainly. Then you can have breakfast.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want breakfast. Can I have the shutters opened please?\'94\
\
The light had been dim in the room and when the shutters were opened it\
was bright sunlight and I looked out on a balcony and beyond were the\
tile roofs of houses and chimneys. I looked out over the tiled roofs and\
saw white clouds and the sky very blue.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you know when the other nurses are coming?\'94\
\
\'93Why? Don\'92t we take good care of you?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re very nice.\'94\
\
\'93Would you like to use the bedpan?\'94\
\
\'93I might try.\'94\
\
They helped me and held me up but it was not any use. Afterward I lay\
and looked out the open doors onto the balcony.\
\
\'93When does the doctor come?\'94\
\
\'93When he gets back. We\'92ve tried to telephone to Lake Como for him.\'94\
\
\'93Aren\'92t there any other doctors?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s the doctor for the hospital.\'94\
\
Miss Gage brought a pitcher of water and a glass. I drank three glasses\
and then they left me and I looked out the window a while and went back\
to sleep. I ate some lunch and in the afternoon Miss Van Campen, the\
superintendent, came up to see me. She did not like me and I did not\
like her. She was small and neatly suspicious and too good for her\
position. She asked many questions and seemed to think it was somewhat\
disgraceful that I was with the Italians.\
\
\'93Can I have wine with the meals?\'94 I asked her.\
\
\'93Only if the doctor prescribes it.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t have it until he comes?\'94\
\
\'93Absolutely not.\'94\
\
\'93You plan on having him come eventually?\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ve telephoned him at Lake Como.\'94\
\
She went out and Miss Gage came back.\
\
\'93Why were you rude to Miss Van Campen?\'94 she asked after she had done\
something for me very skilfully.\
\
\'93I didn\'92t mean to be. But she was snooty.\'94\
\
\'93She said you were domineering and rude.\'94\
\
\'93I wasn\'92t. But what\'92s the idea of a hospital without a doctor?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s coming. They\'92ve telephoned for him to Lake Como.\'94\
\
\'93What does he do there? Swim?\'94\
\
\'93No. He has a clinic there.\'94\
\
\'93Why don\'92t they get another doctor?\'94\
\
\'93Hush. Hush. Be a good boy and he\'92ll come.\'94\
\
I sent for the porter and when he came I told him in Italian to get me a\
bottle of Cinzano at the wine shop, a fiasco of chianti and the evening\
papers. He went away and brought them wrapped in newspaper, unwrapped\
them and, when I asked him to, drew the corks and put the wine and\
vermouth under the bed. They left me alone and I lay in bed and read the\
papers awhile, the news from the front, and the list of dead officers\
with their decorations and then reached down and brought up the bottle\
of Cinzano and held it straight up on my stomach, the cool glass against\
my stomach, and took little drinks making rings on my stomach from\
holding the bottle there between drinks, and watched it get dark outside\
over the roofs of the town. The swallows circled around and I watched\
them and the night-hawks flying above the roofs and drank the Cinzano.\
Miss Gage brought up a glass with some egg-nog in it. I lowered the\
vermouth bottle to the other side of the bed when she came in.\
\
\'93Miss Van Campen had some sherry put in this,\'94 she said. \'93You shouldn\'92t\
be rude to her. She\'92s not young and this hospital is a big\
responsibility for her. Mrs. Walker\'92s too old and she\'92s no use to her.\'94\
\
\'93She\'92s a splendid woman,\'94 I said. \'93Thank her very much.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to bring your supper right away.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s all right,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m not hungry.\'94\
\
When she brought the tray and put it on the bed table I thanked her and\
ate a little of the supper. Afterward it was dark outside and I could\
see the beams of the search-lights moving in the sky. I watched for a\
while and then went to sleep. I slept heavily except once I woke\
sweating and scared and then went back to sleep trying to stay outside\
of my dream. I woke for good long before it was light and heard roosters\
crowing and stayed on awake until it began to be light. I was tired and\
once it was really light I went back to sleep again.\
\
\
\
\
                              CHAPTER XIV\
\
It was bright sunlight in the room when I woke. I thought I was back at\
the front and stretched out in bed. My legs hurt me and I looked down at\
them still in the dirty bandages, and seeing them knew where I was. I\
reached up for the bell-cord and pushed the button. I heard it buzz down\
the hall and then some one coming on rubber soles along the hall. It was\
Miss Gage and she looked a little older in the bright sunlight and not\
so pretty.\
\
\'93Good-morning,\'94 she said. \'93Did you have a good night?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Thanks very much,\'94 I said. \'93Can I have a barber?\'94\
\
\'93I came in to see you and you were asleep with this in the bed with\
you.\'94\
\
She opened the armoire door and held up the vermouth bottle. It was\
nearly empty. \'93I put the other bottle from under the bed in there too,\'94\
she said. \'93Why didn\'92t you ask me for a glass?\'94\
\
\'93I thought maybe you wouldn\'92t let me have it.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d have had some with you.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re a fine girl.\'94\
\
\'93It isn\'92t good for you to drink alone,\'94 she said. \'93You mustn\'92t do it.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Your friend Miss Barkley\'92s come,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93Really?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. I don\'92t like her.\'94\
\
\'93You will like her. She\'92s awfully nice.\'94\
\
She shook her head. \'93I\'92m sure she\'92s fine. Can you move just a little to\
this side? That\'92s fine. I\'92ll clean you up for breakfast.\'94 She washed me\
with a cloth and soap and warm water. \'93Hold your shoulder up,\'94 she said.\
\'93That\'92s fine.\'94\
\
\'93Can I have the barber before breakfast?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll send the porter for him.\'94 She went out and came back. \'93He\'92s gone\
for him,\'94 she said and dipped the cloth she held in the basin of water.\
\
The barber came with the porter. He was a man of about fifty with an\
upturned mustache. Miss Gage was finished with me and went out and the\
barber lathered my face and shaved. He was very solemn and refrained\
from talking.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter? Don\'92t you know any news?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93What news?\'94\
\
\'93Any news. What\'92s happened in the town?\'94\
\
\'93It is time of war,\'94 he said. \'93The enemy\'92s ears are everywhere.\'94\
\
I looked up at him. \'93Please hold your face still,\'94 he said and went on\
shaving. \'93I will tell nothing.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93I am an Italian. I will not communicate with the enemy.\'94\
\
I let it go at that. If he was crazy, the sooner I could get out from\
under the razor the better. Once I tried to get a good look at him.\
\'93Beware,\'94 he said. \'93The razor is sharp.\'94\
\
I paid him when it was over and tipped him half a lira. He returned the\
coins.\
\
\'93I will not. I am not at the front. But I am an Italian.\'94\
\
\'93Get the hell out of here.\'94\
\
\'93With your permission,\'94 he said and wrapped his razors in newspaper. He\
went out leaving the five copper coins on the table beside the bed. I\
rang the bell. Miss Gage came in. \'93Would you ask the porter to come\
please?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
The porter came in. He was trying to keep from laughing.\
\
\'93Is that barber crazy?\'94\
\
\'93No, signorino. He made a mistake. He doesn\'92t understand very well and\
he thought I said you were an Austrian officer.\'94\
\
\'93Oh,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Ho ho ho,\'94 the porter laughed. \'93He was funny. One move from you he said\
and he would have\'97\'94 he drew his forefinger across his throat.\
\
\'93Ho ho ho,\'94 he tried to keep from laughing. \'93When I tell him you were\
not an Austrian. Ho ho ho.\'94\
\
\'93Ho ho ho,\'94 I said bitterly. \'93How funny if he would cut my throat. Ho ho\
ho.\'94\
\
\'93No, signorino. No, no. He was so frightened of an Austrian. Ho ho ho.\'94\
\
\'93Ho ho ho,\'94 I said. \'93Get out of here.\'94\
\
He went out and I heard him laughing in the hall. I heard some one\
coming down the hallway. I looked toward the door. It was Catherine\
Barkley.\
\
She came in the room and over to the bed.\
\
\'93Hello, darling,\'94 she said. She looked fresh and young and very\
beautiful. I thought I had never seen any one so beautiful.\
\
\'93Hello,\'94 I said. When I saw her I was in love with her. Everything\
turned over inside of me. She looked toward the door, saw there was no\
one, then she sat on the side of the bed and leaned over and kissed me.\
I pulled her down and kissed her and felt her heart beating.\
\
\'93You sweet,\'94 I said. \'93Weren\'92t you wonderful to come here?\'94\
\
\'93It wasn\'92t very hard. It may be hard to stay.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ve got to stay,\'94 I said. \'93Oh, you\'92re wonderful.\'94 I was crazy about\
her. I could not believe she was really there and held her tight to me.\
\
\
\
\'93You mustn\'92t,\'94 she said. \'93You\'92re not well enough.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I am. Come on.\'94\
\
\'93No. You\'92re not strong enough.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. I am. Yes. Please.\'94\
\
\'93You do love me?\'94\
\
\'93I really love you. I\'92m crazy about you. Come on please.\'94\
\
\'93Feel our hearts beating.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t care about our hearts. I want you. I\'92m just mad about you.\'94\
\
\'93You really love me?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t keep on saying that. Come on. Please. Please, Catherine.\'94\
\
\'93All right but only for a minute.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93Shut the door.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t. You shouldn\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Come on. Don\'92t talk. Please come on.\'94\
\
\
\
Catherine sat in a chair by the bed. The door was open into the hall.\
The wildness was gone and I felt finer than I had ever felt.\
\
She asked, \'93Now do you believe I love you?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, you\'92re lovely,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92ve got to stay. They can\'92t send you\
away. I\'92m crazy in love with you.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have to be awfully careful. That was just madness. We can\'92t do\
that.\'94\
\
\'93We can at night.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have to be awfully careful. You\'92ll have to be careful in front of\
other people.\'94\
\
\'93I will.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll have to be. You\'92re sweet. You do love me, don\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t say that again. You don\'92t know what that does to me.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll be careful then. I don\'92t want to do anything more to you. I have\
to go now, darling, really.\'94\
\
\'93Come back right away.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll come when I can.\'94\
\
\'93Good-by.\'94\
\
\'93Good-by, sweet.\'94\
\
She went out. God knows I had not wanted to fall in love with her. I had\
not wanted to fall in love with any one. But God knows I had and I lay\
on the bed in the room of the hospital in Milan and all sorts of things\
went through my head but I felt wonderful and finally Miss Gage came in.\
\
\'93The doctor\'92s coming,\'94 she said. \'93He telephoned from Lake Como.\'94\
\
\'93When does he get here?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92ll be here this afternoon.\'94\
\
\
\
\
                               CHAPTER XV\
\
Nothing happened until afternoon. The doctor was a thin quiet little man\
who seemed disturbed by the war. He took out a number of small steel\
splinters from my thighs with delicate and refined distaste. He used a\
local an\'e6sthetic called something or other \'93snow,\'94 which froze the\
tissue and avoided pain until the probe, the scalpel or the forceps got\
below the frozen portion. The an\'e6sthetized area was clearly defined by\
the patient and after a time the doctor\'92s fragile delicacy was exhausted\
and he said it would be better to have an X-ray. Probing was\
unsatisfactory, he said.\
\
The X-ray was taken at the Ospedale Maggiore and the doctor who did it\
was excitable, efficient and cheerful. It was arranged by holding up the\
shoulders, that the patient should see personally some of the larger\
foreign bodies through the machine. The plates were to be sent over. The\
doctor requested me to write in his pocket notebook, my name, and\
regiment and some sentiment. He declared that the foreign bodies were\
ugly, nasty, brutal. The Austrians were sons of bitches. How many had I\
killed? I had not killed any but I was anxious to please\'97and I said I\
had killed plenty. Miss Gage was with me and the doctor put his arm\
around her and said she was more beautiful than Cleopatra. Did she\
understand that? Cleopatra the former queen of Egypt. Yes, by God she\
was. We returned to the little hospital in the ambulance and after a\
while and much lifting I was upstairs and in bed again. The plates came\
that afternoon, the doctor had said by God he would have them that\
afternoon and he did. Catherine Barkley showed them to me. They were in\
red envelopes and she took them out of the envelopes and held them up to\
the light and we both looked.\
\
\'93That\'92s your right leg,\'94 she said, then put the plate back in the\
envelope. \'93This is your left.\'94\
\
\'93Put them away,\'94 I said, \'93and come over to the bed.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t,\'94 she said. \'93I just brought them in for a second to show you.\'94\
\
She went out and I lay there. It was a hot afternoon and I was sick of\
lying in bed. I sent the porter for the papers, all the papers he could\
get.\
\
Before he came back three doctors came into the room. I have noticed\
that doctors who fail in the practice of medicine have a tendency to\
seek one another\'92s company and aid in consultation. A doctor who cannot\
take out your appendix properly will recommend to you a doctor who will\
be unable to remove your tonsils with success. These were three such\
doctors.\
\
\'93This is the young man,\'94 said the house doctor with the delicate hands.\
\
\'93How do you do?\'94 said the tall gaunt doctor with the beard. The third\
doctor, who carried the X-ray plates in their red envelopes, said\
nothing.\
\
\'93Remove the dressings?\'94 questioned the bearded doctor.\
\
\'93Certainly. Remove the dressings, please, nurse,\'94 the house doctor said\
to Miss Gage. Miss Gage removed the dressings. I looked down at the\
legs. At the field hospital they had the look of not too freshly ground\
hamburger steak. Now they were crusted and the knee was swollen and\
discolored and the calf sunken but there was no pus.\
\
\'93Very clean,\'94 said the house doctor. \'93Very clean and nice.\'94\
\
\'93Um,\'94 said the doctor with the beard. The third doctor looked over the\
house doctor\'92s shoulder.\
\
\'93Please move the knee,\'94 said the bearded doctor.\
\
\'93I can\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Test the articulation?\'94 the bearded doctor questioned. He had a stripe\
beside the three stars on his sleeve. That meant he was a first captain.\
\
\'93Certainly,\'94 the house doctor said. Two of them took hold of my right\
leg very gingerly and bent it.\
\
\'93That hurts,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Yes. Yes. A little further, doctor.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s enough. That\'92s as far as it goes,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Partial articulation,\'94 said the first captain. He straightened up. \'93May\
I see the plates again, please, doctor?\'94 The third doctor handed him one\
of the plates. \'93No. The left leg, please.\'94\
\
\'93That is the left leg, doctor.\'94\
\
\'93You are right. I was looking from a different angle.\'94 He returned the\
plate. The other plate he examined for some time. \'93You see, doctor?\'94 he\
pointed to one of the foreign bodies which showed spherical and clear\
against the light. They examined the plate for some time.\
\
\'93Only one thing I can say,\'94 the first captain with the beard said. \'93It\
is a question of time. Three months, six months probably.\'94\
\
\'93Certainly the synovial fluid must re-form.\'94\
\
\'93Certainly. It is a question of time. I could not conscientiously open a\
knee like that before the projectile was encysted.\'94\
\
\'93I agree with you, doctor.\'94\
\
\'93Six months for what?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Six months for the projectile to encyst before the knee can be opened\
safely.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t believe it,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Do you want to keep your knee, young man?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93What?\'94\
\
\'93I want it cut off,\'94 I said, \'93so I can wear a hook on it.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean? A hook?\'94\
\
\'93He is joking,\'94 said the house doctor. He patted my shoulder very\
delicately. \'93He wants to keep his knee. This is a very brave young man.\
He has been proposed for the silver medal of valor.\'94\
\
\'93All my felicitations,\'94 said the first captain. He shook my hand. \'93I can\
only say that to be on the safe side you should wait at least six months\
before opening such a knee. You are welcome of course to another\
opinion.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you very much,\'94 I said. \'93I value your opinion.\'94\
\
The first captain looked at his watch.\
\
\'93We must go,\'94 he said. \'93All my best wishes.\'94\
\
\'93All my best wishes and many thanks,\'94 I said. I shook hands with the\
