                              CHAPTER XXI\
\
In September the first cool nights came, then the days were cool and the\
leaves on the trees in the park began to turn color and we knew the\
summer was gone. The fighting at the front went very badly and they\
could not take San Gabriele. The fighting on the Bainsizza plateau was\
over and by the middle of the month the fighting for San Gabriele was\
about over too. They could not take it. Ettore was gone back to the\
front. The horses were gone to Rome and there was no more racing.\
Crowell had gone to Rome too, to be sent back to America. There were\
riots twice in the town against the war and bad rioting in Turin. A\
British major at the club told me the Italians had lost one hundred and\
fifty thousand men on the Bainsizza plateau and on San Gabriele. He said\
they had lost forty thousand on the Carso besides. We had a drink and he\
talked. He said the fighting was over for the year down here and that\
the Italians had bitten off more than they could chew. He said the\
offensive in Flanders was going to the bad. If they killed men as they\
did this fall the Allies would be cooked in another year. He said we\
were all cooked but we were all right as long as we did not know it. We\
were all cooked. The thing was not to recognize it. The last country to\
realize they were cooked would win the war. We had another drink. Was I\
on somebody\'92s staff? No. He was. It was all balls. We were alone in the\
club sitting back in one of the big leather sofas. His boots were\
smoothly polished dull leather. They were beautiful boots. He said it\
was all balls. They thought only in divisions and man-power. They all\
squabbled about divisions and only killed them when they got them. They\
were all cooked. The Germans won the victories. By God they were\
soldiers. The old Hun was a soldier. But they were cooked too. We were\
all cooked. I asked about Russia. He said they were cooked already. I\'92d\
soon see they were cooked. Then the Austrians were cooked too. If they\
got some Hun divisions they could do it. Did he think they would attack\
this fall? Of course they would. The Italians were cooked. Everybody\
knew they were cooked. The old Hun would come down through the Trentino\
and cut the railway at Vicenza and then where would the Italians be?\
They tried that in \'92sixteen, I said. Not with Germans. Yes, I said. But\
they probably wouldn\'92t do that, he said. It was too simple. They\'92d try\
something complicated and get royally cooked. I had to go, I said. I had\
to get back to the hospital. \'93Good-by,\'94 he said. Then cheerily, \'93Every\
sort of luck!\'94 There was a great contrast between his world pessimism\
and personal cheeriness.\
\
I stopped at a barber shop and was shaved and went home to the hospital.\
My leg was as well as it would get for a long time. I had been up for\
examination three days before. There were still some treatments to take\
before my course at the Ospedale Maggiore was finished and I walked\
along the side street practising not limping. An old man was cutting\
silhouettes under an arcade. I stopped to watch him. Two girls were\
posing and he cut their silhouettes together, snipping very fast and\
looking at them, his head on one side. The girls were giggling. He\
showed me the silhouettes before he pasted them on white paper and\
handed them to the girls.\
\
\'93They\'92re beautiful,\'94 he said. \'93How about you, Tenente?\'94\
\
The girls went away looking at their silhouettes and laughing. They were\
nice-looking girls. One of them worked in the wine shop across from the\
hospital.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Take your cap off.\'94\
\
\'93No. With it on.\'94\
\
\'93It will not be so beautiful,\'94 the old man said. \'93But,\'94 he brightened,\
\'93it will be more military.\'94\
\
He snipped away at the black paper, then separated the two thicknesses\
and pasted the profiles on a card and handed them to me.\
\
\'93How much?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s all right.\'94 He waved his hand. \'93I just made them for you.\'94\
\
\'93Please.\'94 I brought out some coppers. \'93For pleasure.\'94\
\
\'93No. I did them for a pleasure. Give them to your girl.\'94\
\
\'93Many thanks until we meet.\'94\
\
\'93Until I see thee.\'94\
\
I went on to the hospital. There were some letters, an official one, and\
some others. I was to have three weeks\'92 convalescent leave and then\
return to the front. I read it over carefully. Well, that was that. The\
convalescent leave started October fourth when my course was finished.\
Three weeks was twenty-one days. That made October twenty-fifth. I told\
them I would not be in and went to the restaurant a little way up the\
street from the hospital for supper and read my letters and the\
_Corriere Della Sera_ at the table. There was a letter from my\
grandfather, containing family news, patriotic encouragement, a draft\
for two hundred dollars, and a few clippings; a dull letter from the\
priest at our mess, a letter from a man I knew who was flying with the\
French and had gotten in with a wild gang and was telling about it, and\
a note from Rinaldi asking me how long I was going to skulk in Milano\
and what was all the news? He wanted me to bring him phonograph records\
and enclosed a list. I drank a small bottle of chianti with the meal,\
had a coffee afterward with a glass of cognac, finished the paper, put\
my letters in my pocket, left the paper on the table with the tip and\
went out. In my room at the hospital I undressed, put on pajamas and a\
dressing-gown, pulled down the curtains on the door that opened onto the\
balcony and sitting up in bed read Boston papers from a pile Mrs. Meyers\
had left for her boys at the hospital. The Chicago White Sox were\
winning the American League pennant and the New York Giants were leading\
the National League. Babe Ruth was a pitcher then playing for Boston.\
The papers were dull, the news was local and stale, and the war news was\
all old. The American news was all training camps. I was glad I wasn\'92t\
in a training camp. The baseball news was all I could read and I did not\
have the slightest interest in it. A number of papers together made it\
impossible to read with interest. It was not very timely but I read at\
it for a while. I wondered if America really got into the war, if they\
would close down the major leagues. They probably wouldn\'92t. There was\
still racing in Milan and the war could not be much worse. They had\
stopped racing in France. That was where our horse Japalac came from.\
Catherine was not due on duty until nine o\'92clock. I heard her passing\
along the floor when she first came on duty and once saw her pass in the\
hall. She went to several other rooms and finally came into mine.\
\
\'93I\'92m late, darling,\'94 she said. \'93There was a lot to do. How are you?\'94\
\
I told her about my papers and the leave.\
\
\'93That\'92s lovely,\'94 she said. \'93Where do you want to go?\'94\
\
\'93Nowhere. I want to stay here.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s silly. You pick a place to go and I\'92ll come too.\'94\
\
\'93How will you work it?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. But I will.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re pretty wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93No I\'92m not. But life isn\'92t hard to manage when you\'92ve nothing to lose.\'94\
\
\'93How do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing. I was only thinking how small obstacles seemed that once were\
so big.\'94\
\
\'93I should think it might be hard to manage.\'94\
\
\'93No it won\'92t, darling. If necessary I\'92ll simply leave. But it won\'92t come\
to that.\'94\
\
\'93Where should we go?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t care. Anywhere you want. Anywhere we don\'92t know people.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you care where we go?\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92ll like any place.\'94\
\
She seemed upset and taut.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter, Catherine?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing. Nothing\'92s the matter.\'94\
\
\'93Yes there is.\'94\
\
\'93No nothing. Really nothing.\'94\
\
\'93I know there is. Tell me, darling. You can tell me.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s nothing.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to. I\'92m afraid I\'92ll make you unhappy or worry you.\'94\
\
\'93No it won\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re sure? It doesn\'92t worry me but I\'92m afraid to worry you.\'94\
\
\'93It won\'92t if it doesn\'92t worry you.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to tell.\'94\
\
\'93Tell it.\'94\
\
\'93Do I have to?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to have a baby, darling. It\'92s almost three months along.\
You\'92re not worried, are you? Please please don\'92t. You mustn\'92t worry.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Is it all right?\'94\
\
\'93Of course.\'94\
\
\'93I did everything. I took everything but it didn\'92t make any difference.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not worried.\'94\
\
\'93I couldn\'92t help it, darling, and I haven\'92t worried about it. You\
mustn\'92t worry or feel badly.\'94\
\
\'93I only worry about you.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s it. That\'92s what you mustn\'92t do. People have babies all the time.\
Everybody has babies. It\'92s a natural thing.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re pretty wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93No I\'92m not. But you mustn\'92t mind, darling. I\'92ll try and not make\
trouble for you. I know I\'92ve made trouble now. But haven\'92t I been a good\
girl until now? You never knew it, did you?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93It will all be like that. You simply mustn\'92t worry. I can see you\'92re\
worrying. Stop it. Stop it right away. Wouldn\'92t you like a drink,\
darling? I know a drink always makes you feel cheerful.\'94\
\
\'93No. I feel cheerful. And you\'92re pretty wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93No I\'92m not. But I\'92ll fix everything to be together if you pick out a\
place for us to go. It ought to be lovely in October. We\'92ll have a\
lovely time, darling, and I\'92ll write you every day while you\'92re at the\
front.\'94\
\
\'93Where will you be?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know yet. But somewhere splendid. I\'92ll look after all that.\'94\
\
We were quiet awhile and did not talk. Catherine was sitting on the bed\
and I was looking at her but we did not touch each other. We were apart\
as when some one comes into a room and people are self-conscious. She\
put out her hand and took mine.\
\
\'93You aren\'92t angry are you, darling?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93And you don\'92t feel trapped?\'94\
\
\'93Maybe a little. But not by you.\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t mean by me. You mustn\'92t be stupid. I meant trapped at all.\'94\
\
\'93You always feel trapped biologically.\'94\
\
She went away a long way without stirring or removing her hand.\
\
\'93\'91Always\'92 isn\'92t a pretty word.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all right. But you see I\'92ve never had a baby and I\'92ve never even\
loved any one. And I\'92ve tried to be the way you wanted and then you talk\
about \'91always.\'92\'94\
\
\'93I could cut off my tongue,\'94 I offered.\
\
\'93Oh, darling!\'94 she came back from wherever she had been. \'93You mustn\'92t\
mind me.\'94 We were both together again and the self-consciousness was\
gone. \'93We really are the same one and we mustn\'92t misunderstand on\
purpose.\'94\
\
\'93We won\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93But people do. They love each other and they misunderstand on purpose\
and they fight and then suddenly they aren\'92t the same one.\'94\
\
\'93We won\'92t fight.\'94\
\
\'93We mustn\'92t. Because there\'92s only us two and in the world there\'92s all\
the rest of them. If anything comes between us we\'92re gone and then they\
have us.\'94\
\
\'93They won\'92t get us,\'94 I said. \'93Because you\'92re too brave. Nothing ever\
happens to the brave.\'94\
\
\'93They die of course.\'94\
\
\'93But only once.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. Who said that?\'94\
\
\'93The coward dies a thousand deaths, the brave but one?\'94\
\
\'93Of course. Who said it?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93He was probably a coward,\'94 she said. \'93He knew a great deal about\
cowards but nothing about the brave. The brave dies perhaps two thousand\
deaths if he\'92s intelligent. He simply doesn\'92t mention them.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. It\'92s hard to see inside the head of the brave.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. That\'92s how they keep that way.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re an authority.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re right, darling. That was deserved.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re brave.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 she said. \'93But I would like to be.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not,\'94 I said, \'93I know where I stand. I\'92ve been out long enough to\
know. I\'92m like a ball-player that bats two hundred and thirty and knows\
he\'92s no better.\'94\
\
\'93What is a ball-player that bats two hundred and thirty? It\'92s awfully\
impressive.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s not. It means a mediocre hitter in baseball.\'94\
\
\'93But still a hitter,\'94 she prodded me.\
\
\'93I guess we\'92re both conceited,\'94 I said. \'93But you are brave.\'94\
\
\'93No. But I hope to be.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92re both brave,\'94 I said. \'93And I\'92m very brave when I\'92ve had a drink.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92re splendid people,\'94 Catherine said. She went over to the armoire\
and brought me the cognac and a glass. \'93Have a drink, darling,\'94 she\
said. \'93You\'92ve been awfully good.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t really want one.\'94\
\
\'93Take one.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94 I poured the water glass a third full of cognac and drank\
it off.\
\
\'93That was very big,\'94 she said. \'93I know brandy is for heroes. But you\
shouldn\'92t exaggerate.\'94\
\
\'93Where will we live after the war?\'94\
\
\'93In an old people\'92s home probably,\'94 she said. \'93For three years I looked\
forward very childishly to the war ending at Christmas. But now I look\
