\
\'93Maybe he\'92ll be a general.\'94\
\
\'93If it\'92s an hundred years\'92 war he\'92ll have time to try both of the\
services.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want a drink?\'94\
\
\'93No. It always makes you happy, darling, and it only makes me dizzy.\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t you ever drink brandy?\'94\
\
\'93No, darling. I\'92m a very old-fashioned wife.\'94\
\
I reached down to the floor for the bottle and poured another drink.\
\
\'93I\'92d better go to have a look at your compatriots,\'94 Catherine said.\
\'93Perhaps you\'92ll read the papers until I come back.\'94\
\
\'93Do you have to go?\'94\
\
\'93Now or later.\'94\
\
\'93All right. Now.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll come back later.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll have finished the papers,\'94 I said.\
\
