                                BOOK III\
\
\
\
\
                              CHAPTER XXV\
\
Now in the fall the trees were all bare and the roads were muddy. I rode\
to Gorizia from Udine on a camion. We passed other camions on the road\
and I looked at the country. The mulberry trees were bare and the fields\
were brown. There were wet dead leaves on the road from the rows of bare\
trees and men were working on the road, tamping stone in the ruts from\
piles of crushed stone along the side of the road between the trees. We\
saw the town with a mist over it that cut off the mountains. We crossed\
the river and I saw that it was running high. It had been raining in the\
mountains. We came into the town past the factories and then the houses\
and villas and I saw that many more houses had been hit. On a narrow\
street we passed a British Red Cross ambulance. The driver wore a cap\
and his face was thin and very tanned. I did not know him. I got down\
from the camion in the big square in front of the Town Major\'92s house,\
the driver handed down my rucksack and I put it on and swung on the two\
musettes and walked to our villa. It did not feel like a homecoming.\
\
I walked down the damp gravel driveway looking at the villa through the\
trees. The windows were all shut but the door was open. I went in and\
found the major sitting at a table in the bare room with maps and typed\
sheets of paper on the wall.\
\
\'93Hello,\'94 he said. \'93How are you?\'94 He looked older and drier.\
\
\'93I\'92m good,\'94 I said. \'93How is everything?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all over,\'94 he said. \'93Take off your kit and sit down.\'94 I put my\
pack and the two musettes on the floor and my cap on the pack. I brought\
the other chair over from the wall and sat down by the desk.\
\
\'93It\'92s been a bad summer,\'94 the major said. \'93Are you strong now?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Did you ever get the decorations?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. I got them fine. Thank you very much.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s see them.\'94\
\
I opened my cape so he could see the two ribbons.\
\
\'93Did you get the boxes with the medals?\'94\
\
\'93No. Just the papers.\'94\
\
\'93The boxes will come later. That takes more time.\'94\
\
\'93What do you want me to do?\'94\
\
\'93The cars are all away. There are six up north at Caporetto. You know\
Caporetto?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said. I remembered it as a little white town with a campanile\
in a valley. It was a clean little town and there was a fine fountain in\
the square.\
\
\'93They are working from there. There are many sick now. The fighting is\
over.\'94\
\
\'93Where are the others?\'94\
\
\'93There are two up in the mountains and four still on the Bainsizza. The\
other two ambulance sections are in the Carso with the third army.\'94\
\
\'93What do you wish me to do?\'94\
\
\'93You can go and take over the four cars on the Bainsizza if you like.\
Gino has been up there a long time. You haven\'92t seen it up there, have\
you?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93It was very bad. We lost three cars.\'94\
\
\'93I heard about it.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Rinaldi wrote you.\'94\
\
\'93Where is Rinaldi?\'94\
\
\'93He is here at the hospital. He has had a summer and fall of it.\'94\
\
\'93I believe it.\'94\
\
\'93It has been bad,\'94 the major said. \'93You couldn\'92t believe how bad it\'92s\
been. I\'92ve often thought you were lucky to be hit when you were.\'94\
\
\'93I know I was.\'94\
\
\'93Next year will be worse,\'94 the major said. \'93Perhaps they will attack\
now. They say they are to attack but I can\'92t believe it. It is too late.\
You saw the river?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. It\'92s high already.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t believe they will attack now that the rains have started. We\
will have the snow soon. What about your countrymen? Will there be other\
Americans besides yourself?\'94\
\
\'93They are training an army of ten million.\'94\
\
\'93I hope we get some of them. But the French will hog them all. We\'92ll\
never get any down here. All right. You stay here to-night and go out\
to-morrow with the little car and send Gino back. I\'92ll send somebody\
with you that knows the road. Gino will tell you everything. They are\
shelling quite a little still but it is all over. You will want to see\
the Bainsizza.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m glad to see it. I am glad to be back with you again, Signor\
Maggiore.\'94\
\
He smiled. \'93You are very good to say so. I am very tired of this war. If\
I was away I do not believe I would come back.\'94\
\
\'93Is it so bad?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. It is so bad and worse. Go get cleaned up and find your friend\
Rinaldi.\'94\
\
I went out and carried my bags up the stairs. Rinaldi was not in the\
room but his things were there and I sat down on the bed and unwrapped\
my puttees and took the shoe off my right foot. Then I lay back on the\
bed. I was tired and my right foot hurt. It seemed silly to lie on the\
bed with one shoe off, so I sat up and unlaced the other shoe and\
dropped it on the floor, then lay back on the blanket again. The room\
was stuffy with the window closed but I was too tired to get up and open\
it. I saw my things were all in one corner of the room. Outside it was\
getting dark. I lay on the bed and thought about Catherine and waited\
for Rinaldi. I was going to try not to think about Catherine except at\
night before I went to sleep. But now I was tired and there was nothing\
to do, so I lay and thought about her. I was thinking about her when\
Rinaldi came in. He looked just the same. Perhaps he was a little\
thinner.\
\
\'93Well, baby,\'94 he said. I sat up on the bed. He came over, sat down and\
put his arm around me. \'93Good old baby.\'94 He whacked me on the back and I\
held both his arms.\
\
\'93Old baby,\'94 he said. \'93Let me see your knee.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll have to take off my pants.\'94\
\
\'93Take off your pants, baby. We\'92re all friends here. I want to see what\
kind of a job they did.\'94 I stood up, took off the breeches and pulled\
off the knee-brace. Rinaldi sat on the floor and bent the knee gently\
back and forth. He ran his finger along the scar; put his thumbs\
together over the kneecap and rocked the knee gently with his fingers.\
\
\'93Is that all the articulation you have?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a crime to send you back. They ought to get complete\
articulation.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lot better than it was. It was stiff as a board.\'94\
\
Rinaldi bent it more. I watched his hands. He had fine surgeon\'92s hands.\
I looked at the top of his head, his hair shiny and parted smoothly. He\
bent the knee too far.\
\
\'93Ouch!\'94 I said.\
\
\'93You ought to have more treatment on it with the machines,\'94 Rinaldi\
said.\
\
\'93It\'92s better than it was.\'94\
\
\'93I see that, baby. This is something I know more about than you.\'94 He\
stood up and sat down on the bed. \'93The knee itself is a good job.\'94 He\
was through with the knee. \'93Tell me all about everything.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s nothing to tell,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ve led a quiet life.\'94\
\
\'93You act like a married man,\'94 he said. \'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing,\'94 I said. \'93What\'92s the matter with you?\'94\
\
\'93This war is killing me,\'94 Rinaldi said, \'93I am very depressed by it.\'94 He\
folded his hands over his knee.\
\
\'93Oh,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter? Can\'92t I even have human impulses?\'94\
\
\'93No. I can see you\'92ve been having a fine time. Tell me.\'94\
\
\'93All summer and all fall I\'92ve operated. I work all the time. I do\
everybody\'92s work. All the hard ones they leave to me. By God, baby, I am\
becoming a lovely surgeon.\'94\
\
\'93That sounds better.\'94\
\
\'93I never think. No, by God, I don\'92t think; I operate.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s right.\'94\
\
\'93But now, baby, it\'92s all over. I don\'92t operate now and I feel like hell.\
This is a terrible war, baby. You believe me when I say it. Now you\
cheer me up. Did you bring the phonograph records?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
They were wrapped in paper in a cardboard box in my rucksack. I was too\
tired to get them out.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you feel good yourself, baby?\'94\
\
\'93I feel like hell.\'94\
\
\'93This war is terrible,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93Come on. We\'92ll both get drunk and\
be cheerful. Then we\'92ll go get the ashes dragged. Then we\'92ll feel fine.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve had the jaundice,\'94 I said, \'93and I can\'92t get drunk.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, baby, how you\'92ve come back to me. You come back serious and with a\
liver. I tell you this war is a bad thing. Why did we make it anyway?\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have a drink. I don\'92t want to get drunk but we\'92ll have a drink.\'94\
\
Rinaldi went across the room to the washstand and brought back two\
glasses and a bottle of cognac.\
\
\'93It\'92s Austrian cognac,\'94 he said. \'93Seven stars. It\'92s all they captured on\
San Gabriele.\'94\
\
\'93Were you up there?\'94\
\
\'93No. I haven\'92t been anywhere. I\'92ve been here all the time operating.\
Look, baby, this is your old toothbrushing glass. I kept it all the time\
to remind me of you.\'94\
\
\'93To remind you to brush your teeth.\'94\
\
\'93No. I have my own too. I kept this to remind me of you trying to brush\
away the Villa Rossa from your teeth in the morning, swearing and eating\
aspirin and cursing harlots. Every time I see that glass I think of you\
trying to clean your conscience with a toothbrush.\'94 He came over to the\
bed. \'93Kiss me once and tell me you\'92re not serious.\'94\
\
\'93I never kiss you. You\'92re an ape.\'94\
\
\'93I know, you are the fine good Anglo-Saxon boy. I know. You are the\
remorse boy, I know. I will wait till I see the Anglo-Saxon brushing\
away harlotry with a toothbrush.\'94\
\
\'93Put some cognac in the glass.\'94\
\
We touched glasses and drank. Rinaldi laughed at me.\
\
\'93I will get you drunk and take out your liver and put you in a good\
Italian liver and make you a man again.\'94\
\
I held the glass for some more cognac. It was dark outside now. Holding\
the glass of cognac, I went over and opened the window. The rain had\
stopped falling. It was colder outside and there was a mist in the\
trees.\
\
\'93Don\'92t throw the cognac out the window,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93If you can\'92t\
drink it give it to me.\'94\
\
\'93Go something yourself,\'94 I said. I was glad to see Rinaldi again. He had\
spent two years teasing me and I had always liked it. We understood each\
other very well.\
\
\'93Are you married?\'94 he asked from the bed. I was standing against the\
wall by the window.\
\
\'93Not yet.\'94\
\
\'93Are you in love?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93With that English girl?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Poor baby. Is she good to you?\'94\
\
\'93Of course.\'94\
\
\'93I mean is she good to you practically speaking?\'94\
\
\'93Shut up.\'94\
\
\'93I will. You will see I am a man of extreme delicacy. Does she\'97\'97?\'94\
\
\'93Rinin,\'94 I said. \'93Please shut up. If you want to be my friend, shut up.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t _want_ to be your friend, baby. I _am_ your friend.\'94\
\
\'93Then shut up.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
I went over to the bed and sat down beside Rinaldi. He was holding his\
glass and looking at the floor.\
\
\'93You see how it is, Rinin?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. All my life I encounter sacred subjects. But very few with\
you. I suppose you must have them too.\'94 He looked at the floor.\
\
\'93You haven\'92t any?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Not any?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93I can say this about your mother and that about your sister?\'94\
\
\'93And that about _your sister_,\'94 Rinaldi said swiftly. We both laughed.\
\
\'93The old superman,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I am jealous maybe,\'94 Rinaldi said.\
\
\'93No, you\'92re not.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t mean like that. I mean something else. Have you any married\
friends?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I haven\'92t,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93Not if they love each other.\'94\
\
\'93Why not?\'94\
\
\'93They don\'92t like me.\'94\
\
\'93Why not?\'94\
\
\'93I am the snake. I am the snake of reason.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re getting it mixed. The apple was reason.\'94\
\
\'93No, it was the snake.\'94 He was more cheerful.\
\
\'93You are better when you don\'92t think so deeply,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I love you, baby,\'94 he said. \'93You puncture me when I become a great\
Italian thinker. But I know many things I can\'92t say. I know more than\
you.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. You do.\'94\
\
\'93But you will have a better time. Even with remorse you will have a\
better time.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think so.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. That is true. Already I am only happy when I am working.\'94 He\
looked at the floor again.\
\
\'93You\'92ll get over that.\'94\
\
\'93No. I only like two other things; one is bad for my work and the other\
is over in half an hour or fifteen minutes. Sometimes less.\'94\
\
\'93Sometimes a good deal less.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps I have improved, baby. You do not know. But there are only the\
two things and my work.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll get other things.\'94\
\
\'93No. We never get anything. We are born with all we have and we never\
learn. We never get anything new. We all start complete. You should be\
glad not to be a Latin.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no such thing as a Latin. That is \'91Latin\'92 thinking. You are so\
proud of your defects.\'94 Rinaldi looked up and laughed.\
\
\'93We\'92ll stop, baby. I am tired from thinking so much.\'94 He had looked\
tired when he came in. \'93It\'92s nearly time to eat. I\'92m glad you\'92re back.\
You are my best friend and my war brother.\'94\
\
\'93When do the war brothers eat?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Right away. We\'92ll drink once more for your liver\'92s sake.\'94\
\
\'93Like Saint Paul.\'94\
\
\'93You are inaccurate. That was wine and the stomach. Take a little wine\
for your stomach\'92s sake.\'94\
\
\'93Whatever you have in the bottle,\'94 I said. \'93For any sake you mention.\'94\
\
\'93To your girl,\'94 Rinaldi said. He held out his glass.\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll never say a dirty thing about her.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t strain yourself.\'94\
\
He drank off the cognac. \'93I am pure,\'94 he said. \'93I am like you, baby. I\
will get an English girl too. As a matter of fact I knew your girl first\
but she was a little tall for me. A tall girl for a sister,\'94 he quoted.\
\
\'93You have a lovely pure mind,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Haven\'92t I? That\'92s why they call me Rinaldo Purissimo.\'94\
\
\'93Rinaldo Sporchissimo.\'94\
\
\'93Come on, baby, we\'92ll go down to eat while my mind is still pure.\'94\
\
I washed, combed my hair and we went down the stairs. Rinaldi was a\
little drunk. In the room where we ate, the meal was not quite ready.\
\
\'93I\'92ll go get the bottle,\'94 Rinaldi said. He went off up the stairs. I sat\
at the table and he came back with the bottle and poured us each a half\
tumbler of cognac.\
\
\'93Too much,\'94 I said and held up the glass and sighted at the lamp on the\
table.\
\
\'93Not for an empty stomach. It is a wonderful thing. It burns out the\
stomach completely. Nothing is worse for you.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Self-destruction day by day,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93It ruins the stomach and\
makes the hand shake. Just the thing for a surgeon.\'94\
\
\'93You recommend it?\'94\
\
\'93Heartily. I use no other. Drink it down, baby, and look forward to\
being sick.\'94\
\
I drank half the glass. In the hall I could hear the orderly calling.\
\'93Soup! Soup is ready!\'94\
\
The major came in, nodded to us and sat down. He seemed very small at\
table.\
\
\'93Is this all we are?\'94 he asked. The orderly put the soup bowl down and\
he ladled out a plate full.\
\
\'93We are all,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93Unless the priest comes. If he knew\
Federico was here he would be here.\'94\
\
\'93Where is he?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93He\'92s at 307,\'94 the major said. He was busy with his soup. He wiped his\
mouth, wiping his upturned gray mustache carefully. \'93He will come I\
think. I called them and left word to tell him you were here.\'94\
\
\'93I miss the noise of the mess,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Yes, it\'92s quiet,\'94 the major said.\
\
\'93I will be noisy,\'94 said Rinaldi.\
\
\'93Drink some wine, Enrico,\'94 said the major. He filled my glass. The\
spaghetti came in and we were all busy. We were finishing the spaghetti\
when the priest came in. He was the same as ever, small and brown and\
compact looking. I stood up and we shook hands. He put his hand on my\
shoulder.\
\
\'93I came as soon as I heard,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Sit down,\'94 the major said. \'93You\'92re late.\'94\
\
\'93Good-evening, priest,\'94 Rinaldi said, using the English word. They had\
taken that up from the priest-baiting captain, who spoke a little\
English. \'93Good-evening, Rinaldo,\'94 the priest said. The orderly brought\
him soup but he said he would start with the spaghetti.\
\
\'93How are you?\'94 he asked me.\
\
\'93Fine,\'94 I said. \'93How have things been?\'94\
\
\'93Drink some wine, priest,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93Take a little wine for your\
stomach\'92s sake. That\'92s Saint Paul, you know.\'94\
\
\'93Yes I know,\'94 said the priest politely. Rinaldi filled his glass.\
\
\'93That Saint Paul,\'94 said Rinaldi. \'93He\'92s the one who makes all the\
trouble.\'94 The priest looked at me and smiled. I could see that the\
baiting did not touch him now.\
\
\'93That Saint Paul,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93He was a rounder and a chaser and then\
when he was no longer hot he said it was no good. When he was finished\
he made the rules for us who are still hot. Isn\'92t it true, Federico?\'94\
\
The major smiled. We were eating meat stew now.\
\
\'93I never discuss a Saint after dark,\'94 I said. The priest looked up from\
the stew and smiled at me.\
\
\'93There he is, gone over with the priest,\'94 Rinaldi said. \'93Where are all\
the good old priest-baiters? Where is Cavalcanti? Where is Brundi? Where\
is Cesare? Do I have to bait this priest alone without support?\'94\
\
\'93He is a good priest,\'94 said the major.\
\
\'93He is a good priest,\'94 said Rinaldi. \'93But still a priest. I try to make\
the mess like the old days. I want to make Federico happy. To hell with\
you, priest!\'94\
\
I saw the major look at him and notice that he was drunk. His thin face\
was white. The line of his hair was very black against the white of his\
forehead.\
\
\'93It\'92s all right, Rinaldo,\'94 said the priest. \'93It\'92s all right.\'94\
\
\'93To hell with you,\'94 said Rinaldi. \'93To hell with the whole damn\
business.\'94 He sat back in his chair.\
\
\'93He\'92s been under a strain and he\'92s tired,\'94 the major said to me. He\
finished his meat and wiped up the gravy with a piece of bread.\
\
\'93I don\'92t give a damn,\'94 Rinaldi said to the table. \'93To hell with the\
whole business.\'94 He looked defiantly around the table, his eyes flat,\
his face pale.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93To hell with the whole damn business.\'94\
\
\'93No, no,\'94 said Rinaldi. \'93You can\'92t do it. You can\'92t do it. I say you\
can\'92t do it. You\'92re dry and you\'92re empty and there\'92s nothing else.\
There\'92s nothing else I tell you. Not a damned thing. I know, when I stop\
working.\'94\
\
The priest shook his head. The orderly took away the stew dish.\
\
\'93What are you eating meat for?\'94 Rinaldi turned to the priest. \'93Don\'92 you\
know it\'92s Friday?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s Thursday,\'94 the priest said.\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie. It\'92s Friday. You\'92re eating the body of our Lord. It\'92s\
God-meat. I know. It\'92s dead Austrian. That\'92s what you\'92re eating.\'94\
\
\'93The white meat is from officers,\'94 I said, completing the old joke.\
\
Rinaldi laughed. He filled his glass.\
\
\'93Don\'92t mind me,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m just a little crazy.\'94\
\
\'93You ought to have a leave,\'94 the priest said.\
\
The major shook his head at him. Rinaldi looked at the priest.\
\
\'93You think I ought to have a leave?\'94\
\
The major shook his head at the priest. Rinaldi was looking at the\
priest.\
\
\'93Just as you like,\'94 the priest said. \'93Not if you don\'92t want.\'94\
\
