the officers\'92 house had left early that morning, she said. Where were\
they going? To Conegliano, she said. The truck started. The girl with\
thick lips put out her tongue again at us. The matron waved. The two\
girls kept on crying. The others looked interestedly out at the town. I\
got back in the car.\
\
\'93We ought to go with them,\'94 Bonello said. \'93That would be a good trip.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have a good trip,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We\'92ll have a hell of a trip.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s what I mean,\'94 I said. We came up the drive to the villa.\
\
\'93I\'92d like to be there when some of those tough babies climb in and try\
and hop them.\'94\
\
\'93You think they will?\'94\
\
\'93Sure. Everybody in the Second Army knows that matron.\'94\
\
We were outside the villa.\
\
\'93They call her the Mother Superior,\'94 Bonello said. \'93The girls are new\
but everybody knows her. They must have brought them up just before the\
retreat.\'94\
