                                BOOK IV\
\
\
\
\
                             CHAPTER XXXIII\
\
I dropped off the train in Milan as it slowed to come into the station\
early in the morning before it was light. I crossed the track and came\
out between some buildings and down onto the street. A wine shop was\
open and I went in for some coffee. It smelled of early morning, of\
swept dust, spoons in coffee-glasses and the wet circles left by\
wine-glasses. The proprietor was behind the bar. Two soldiers sat at a\
table. I stood at the bar and drank a glass of coffee and ate a piece of\
bread. The coffee was gray with milk, and I skimmed the milk scum off\
the top with a piece of bread. The proprietor looked at me.\
\
\'93You want a glass of grappa?\'94\
\
\'93No thanks.\'94\
\
\'93On me,\'94 he said and poured a small glass and pushed it toward me.\
\'93What\'92s happening at the front?\'94\
\
\'93I would not know.\'94\
\
\'93They are drunk,\'94 he said, moving his hand toward the two soldiers. I\
could believe him. They looked drunk.\
\
\'93Tell me,\'94 he said, \'93what is happening at the front?\'94\
\
\'93I would not know about the front.\'94\
\
\'93I saw you come down the wall. You came off the train.\'94\
\
\'93There is a big retreat.\'94\
\
\'93I read the papers. What happens? Is it over?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think so.\'94\
\
He filled the glass with grappa from a short bottle. \'93If you are in\
trouble,\'94 he said, \'93I can keep you.\'94\
\
\'93I am not in trouble.\'94\
\
\'93If you are in trouble stay here with me.\'94\
\
\'93Where does one stay?\'94\
\
\'93In the building. Many stay here. Any who are in trouble stay here.\'94\
\
\'93Are many in trouble?\'94\
\
\'93It depends on the trouble. You are a South American?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Speak Spanish?\'94\
\
\'93A little.\'94\
\
He wiped off the bar.\
\
\'93It is hard now to leave the country but in no way impossible.\'94\
\
\'93I have no wish to leave.\'94\
\
\'93You can stay here as long as you want. You will see what sort of man I\
am.\'94\
\
\'93I have to go this morning but I will remember the address to return.\'94\
\
He shook his head. \'93You won\'92t come back if you talk like that. I thought\
you were in real trouble.\'94\
\
\'93I am in no trouble. But I value the address of a friend.\'94\
\
I put a ten-lira note on the bar to pay for the coffee.\
\
\'93Have a grappa with me,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93It is not necessary.\'94\
\
\'93Have one.\'94\
\
He poured the two glasses.\
\
\'93Remember,\'94 he said. \'93Come here. Do not let other people take you in.\
Here you are all right.\'94\
\
\'93I am sure.\'94\
\
\'93You are sure?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
He was serious. \'93Then let me tell you one thing. Do not go about with\
that coat.\'94\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93On the sleeves it shows very plainly where the stars have been cut\
away. The cloth is a different color.\'94\
\
I did not say anything.\
\
\'93If you have no papers I can give you papers.\'94\
\
\'93What papers?\'94\
\
\'93Leave-papers.\'94\
\
\'93I have no need for papers. I have papers.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 he said. \'93But if you need papers I can get what you wish.\'94\
\
\'93How much are such papers?\'94\
\
\'93It depends on what they are. The price is reasonable.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t need any now.\'94\
\
He shrugged his shoulders.\
\
\'93I\'92m all right,\'94 I said.\
\
When I went out he said, \'93Don\'92t forget that I am your friend.\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93I will see you again,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Good,\'94 I said.\
\
