                             CHAPTER XXXIV\
\
In civilian clothes I felt a masquerader. I had been in uniform a long\
time and I missed the feeling of being held by your clothes. The\
trousers felt very floppy. I had bought a ticket at Milan for Stresa. I\
had also bought a new hat. I could not wear Sim\'92s hat but his clothes\
were fine. They smelled of tobacco and as I sat in the compartment and\
looked out the window the new hat felt very new and the clothes very\
old. I myself felt as sad as the wet Lombard country that was outside\
through the window. There were some aviators in the compartment who did\
not think much of me. They avoided looking at me and were very scornful\
of a civilian my age. I did not feel insulted. In the old days I would\
have insulted them and picked a fight. They got off at Gallarate and I\
was glad to be alone. I had the paper but I did not read it because I\
did not want to read about the war. I was going to forget the war. I had\
made a separate peace. I felt damned lonely and was glad when the train\
got to Stresa.\
\
At the station I had expected to see the porters from the hotels but\
there was no one. The season had been over a long time and no one met\
the train. I got down from the train with my bag, it was Sim\'92s bag, and\
very light to carry, being empty except for two shirts, and stood under\
the roof of the station in the rain while the train went on. I found a\
man in the station and asked him if he knew what hotels were open. The\
Grand-H\'f4tel & des Isles Borrom\'e9es was open and several small hotels that\
stayed open all the year. I started in the rain for the Isles Borrom\'e9es\
carrying my bag. I saw a carriage coming down the street and signalled\
to the driver. It was better to arrive in a carriage. We drove up to the\
carriage entrance of the big hotel and the concierge came out with an\
umbrella and was very polite.\
\
I took a good room. It was very big and light and looked out on the\
lake. The clouds were down over the lake but it would be beautiful with\
the sunlight. I was expecting my wife, I said. There was a big double\
bed, a _letto matrimoniale_ with a satin coverlet. The hotel was very\
luxurious. I went down the long halls, down the wide stairs, through the\
rooms to the bar. I knew the barman and sat on a high stool and ate\
salted almonds and potato chips. The martini felt cool and clean.\
\
\'93What are you doing here in _borghese_?\'94 the barman asked after he had\
mixed a second martini.\
\
\'93I am on leave. Convalescing-leave.\'94\
\
\'93There is no one here. I don\'92t know why they keep the hotel open.\'94\
\
\'93Have you been fishing?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve caught some beautiful pieces. Trolling this time of year you catch\
some beautiful pieces.\'94\
\
\'93Did you ever get the tobacco I sent?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Didn\'92t you get my card?\'94\
\
I laughed. I had not been able to get the tobacco. It was American\
pipe-tobacco that he wanted, but my relatives had stopped sending it or\
it was being held up. Anyway it never came.\
\
\'93I\'92ll get some somewhere,\'94 I said. \'93Tell me have you seen two English\
girls in the town? They came here day before yesterday.\'94\
\
\'93They are not at the hotel.\'94\
\
\'93They are nurses.\'94\
\
\'93I have seen two nurses. Wait a minute, I will find out where they are.\'94\
\
\'93One of them is my wife,\'94 I said. \'93I have come here to meet her.\'94\
\
\'93The other is my wife.\'94\
\
\'93I am not joking.\'94\
\
\'93Pardon my stupid joke,\'94 he said. \'93I did not understand.\'94 He went away\
and was gone quite a little while. I ate olives, salted almonds and\
potato chips and looked at myself in civilian clothes in the mirror\
behind the bar. The bartender came back. \'93They are at the little hotel\
near the station,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93How about some sandwiches?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll ring for some. You understand there is nothing here, now there are\
no people.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t there really any one at all?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. There are a few people.\'94\
\
The sandwiches came and I ate three and drank a couple more martinis. I\
had never tasted anything so cool and clean. They made me feel\
civilized. I had had too much red wine, bread, cheese, bad coffee and\
grappa. I sat on the high stool before the pleasant mahogany, the brass\
and the mirrors and did not think at all. The barman asked me some\
question.\
\
\'93Don\'92t talk about the war,\'94 I said. The war was a long way away. Maybe\
there wasn\'92t any war. There was no war here. Then I realized it was over\
for me. But I did not have the feeling that it was really over. I had\
the feeling of a boy who thinks of what is happening at a certain hour\
at the schoolhouse from which he has played truant.\
\
\
\
Catherine and Helen Ferguson were at supper when I came to their hotel.\
Standing in the hallway I saw them at table. Catherine\'92s face was away\
from me and I saw the line of her hair and her cheek and her lovely neck\
and shoulders. Ferguson was talking. She stopped when I came in.\
\
\'93My God,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93Hello,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Why it\'92s you!\'94 Catherine said. Her face lighted up. She looked too\
happy to believe it. I kissed her. Catherine blushed and I sat down at\
the table.\
\
\'93You\'92re a fine mess,\'94 Ferguson said. \'93What are you doing here? Have you\
eaten?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94 The girl who was serving the meal came in and I told her to bring\
a plate for me. Catherine looked at me all the time, her eyes happy.\
\
\'93What are you doing in mufti?\'94 Ferguson asked.\
\
\'93I\'92m in the Cabinet.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re in some mess.\'94\
\
\'93Cheer up, Fergy. Cheer up just a little.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not cheered by seeing you. I know the mess you\'92ve gotten this girl\
into. You\'92re no cheerful sight to me.\'94\
\
Catherine smiled at me and touched me with her foot under the table.\
\
\'93No one got me in a mess, Fergy. I get in my own messes.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t stand him,\'94 Ferguson said. \'93He\'92s done nothing but ruin you with\
his sneaking Italian tricks. Americans are worse than Italians.\'94\
\
\'93The Scotch are such a moral people,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93I don\'92t mean that. I mean his Italian sneakiness.\'94\
\
\'93Am I sneaky, Fergy?\'94\
\
\'93You are. You\'92re worse than sneaky. You\'92re like a snake. A snake with an\
Italian uniform: with a cape around your neck.\'94\
\
\'93I haven\'92t got an Italian uniform now.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s just another example of your sneakiness. You had a love affair\
all summer and got this girl with child and now I suppose you\'92ll sneak\
off.\'94\
\
I smiled at Catherine and she smiled at me.\
\
\'93We\'92ll both sneak off,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93You\'92re two of the same thing,\'94 Ferguson said. \'93I\'92m ashamed of you,\
Catherine Barkley. You have no shame and no honor and you\'92re as sneaky\
as he is.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t, Fergy,\'94 Catherine said and patted her hand. \'93Don\'92t denounce me.\
You know we like each other.\'94\
\
\'93Take your hand away,\'94 Ferguson said. Her face was red. \'93If you had any\
shame it would be different. But you\'92re God knows how many months gone\
with child and you think it\'92s a joke and are all smiles because your\
seducer\'92s come back. You\'92ve no shame and no feelings.\'94 She began to cry.\
Catherine went over and put her arm around her. As she stood comforting\
Ferguson, I could see no change in her figure.\
\
\'93I don\'92t care,\'94 Ferguson sobbed. \'93I think it\'92s dreadful.\'94\
\
\'93There, there, Fergy,\'94 Catherine comforted her. \'93I\'92ll be ashamed. Don\'92t\
cry, Fergy. Don\'92t cry, old Fergy.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not crying,\'94 Ferguson sobbed. \'93I\'92m not crying. Except for the awful\
thing you\'92ve gotten into.\'94 She looked at me. \'93I hate you,\'94 she said.\
\'93She can\'92t make me not hate you. You dirty sneaking American Italian.\'94\
Her eyes and nose were red with crying.\
\
Catherine smiled at me.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you smile at him with your arm around me.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re unreasonable, Fergy.\'94\
\
\'93I know it,\'94 Ferguson sobbed. \'93You mustn\'92t mind me, either of you. I\'92m\
so upset. I\'92m not reasonable. I know it. I want you both to be happy.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92re happy,\'94 Catherine said. \'93You\'92re a sweet Fergy.\'94\
\
Ferguson cried again. \'93I don\'92t want you happy the way you are. Why don\'92t\
you get married? You haven\'92t got another wife have you?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. Catherine laughed.\
\
\'93It\'92s nothing to laugh about,\'94 Ferguson said. \'93Plenty of them have other\
wives.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll be married, Fergy,\'94 Catherine said, \'93if it will please you.\'94\
\
\'93Not to please me. You should want to be married.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ve been very busy.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. I know. Busy making babies.\'94 I thought she was going to cry again\
but she went into bitterness instead. \'93I suppose you\'92ll go off with him\
now to-night?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 said Catherine. \'93If he wants me.\'94\
\
\'93What about me?\'94\
\
\'93Are you afraid to stay here alone?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I am.\'94\
\
\'93Then I\'92ll stay with you.\'94\
\
\'93No, go on with him. Go with him right away. I\'92m sick of seeing both of\
you.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92d better finish dinner.\'94\
\
\'93No. Go right away.\'94\
\
\'93Fergy, be reasonable.\'94\
\
\'93I say get out right away. Go away both of you.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s go then,\'94 I said. I was sick of Fergy.\
\
\'93You do want to go. You see you want to leave me even to eat dinner\
alone. I\'92ve always wanted to go to the Italian lakes and this is how it\
is. Oh, Oh,\'94 she sobbed, then looked at Catherine and choked.\
\
\'93We\'92ll stay till after dinner,\'94 Catherine said. \'93And I\'92ll not leave you\
alone if you want me to stay. I won\'92t leave you alone, Fergy.\'94\
\
\'93No. No. I want you to go. I want you to go.\'94 She wiped her eyes. \'93I\'92m\
so unreasonable. Please don\'92t mind me.\'94\
\
The girl who served the meal had been upset by all the crying. Now as\
she brought in the next course she seemed relieved that things were\
better.\
\
\
\
That night at the hotel, in our room with the long empty hall outside\
and our shoes outside the door, a thick carpet on the floor of the room,\
outside the windows the rain falling and in the room light and pleasant\
and cheerful, then the light out and it exciting with smooth sheets and\
the bed comfortable, feeling that we had come home, feeling no longer\
alone, waking in the night to find the other one there, and not gone\
away; all other things were unreal. We slept when we were tired and if\
we woke the other one woke too so one was not alone. Often a man wishes\
to be alone and a girl wishes to be alone too and if they love each\
other they are jealous of that in each other, but I can truly say we\
never felt that. We could feel alone when we were together, alone\
against the others. It has only happened to me like that once. I have\
been alone while I was with many girls and that is the way that you can\
be most lonely. But we were never lonely and never afraid when we were\
together. I know that the night is not the same as the day: that all\
things are different, that the things of the night cannot be explained\
in the day, because they do not then exist, and the night can be a\
dreadful time for lonely people once their loneliness has started. But\
with Catherine there was almost no difference in the night except that\
it was an even better time. If people bring so much courage to this\
world the world has to kill them to break them, so of course it kills\
them. The world breaks every one and afterward many are strong at the\
broken places. But those that will not break it kills. It kills the very\
good and the very gentle and the very brave impartially. If you are none\
of these you can be sure it will kill you too but there will be no\
special hurry.\
\
\
\
I remember waking in the morning. Catherine was asleep and the sunlight\
was coming in through the window. The rain had stopped and I stepped out\
of bed and across the floor to the window. Down below were the gardens,\
bare now but beautifully regular, the gravel paths, the trees, the stone\
wall by the lake and the lake in the sunlight with the mountains beyond.\
I stood at the window looking out and when I turned away I saw Catherine\
was awake and watching me.\
\
\'93How are you, darling?\'94 she said. \'93Isn\'92t it a lovely day?\'94\
\
\'93How do you feel?\'94\
\
\'93I feel very well. We had a lovely night.\'94\
\
\'93Do you want breakfast?\'94\
\
She wanted breakfast. So did I and we had it in bed, the November\
sunlight coming in the window, and the breakfast tray across my lap.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want the paper? You always wanted the paper in the hospital.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I don\'92t want the paper now.\'94\
\
\'93Was it so bad you don\'92t want even to read about it?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to read about it.\'94\
\
\'93I wish I had been with you so I would know about it too.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you about it if I ever get it straight in my head.\'94\
\
\'93But won\'92t they arrest you if they catch you out of uniform?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92ll probably shoot me.\'94\
\
\'93Then we\'92ll not stay here. We\'92ll get out of the country.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d thought something of that.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll get out. Darling, you shouldn\'92t take silly chances. Tell me how\
did you come from Mestre to Milan?\'94\
\
\'93I came on the train. I was in uniform then.\'94\
\
\'93Weren\'92t you in danger then?\'94\
\
\'93Not much. I had an old order of movement. I fixed the dates on it in\
Mestre.\'94\
\
\'93Darling, you\'92re liable to be arrested here any time. I won\'92t have it.\
It\'92s silly to do something like that. Where would we be if they took you\
off?\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s not think about it. I\'92m tired of thinking about it.\'94\
\
\'93What would you do if they came to arrest you?\'94\
\
\'93Shoot them.\'94\
\
\'93You see how silly you are, I won\'92t let you go out of the hotel until we\
leave here.\'94\
\
\'93Where are we going to go?\'94\
\
\'93Please don\'92t be that way, darling. We\'92ll go wherever you say. But\
please find some place to go right away.\'94\
\
\'93Switzerland is down the lake, we can go there.\'94\
\
\'93That will be lovely.\'94\
\
It was clouding over outside and the lake was darkening.\
\
\'93I wish we did not always have to live like criminals,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Darling, don\'92t be that way. You haven\'92t lived like a criminal very\
long. And we never live like criminals. We\'92re going to have a fine\
time.\'94\
\
\'93I feel like a criminal. I\'92ve deserted from the army.\'94\
\
\'93Darling, _please_ be sensible. It\'92s not deserting from the army. It\'92s\
only the Italian army.\'94\
\
I laughed. \'93You\'92re a fine girl. Let\'92s get back into bed. I feel fine in\
bed.\'94\
\
\
\
A little while later Catherine said, \'93You don\'92t feel like a criminal do\
you?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93Not when I\'92m with you.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re such a silly boy,\'94 she said. \'93But I\'92ll look after you. Isn\'92t it\
splendid, darling, that I don\'92t have any morning-sickness?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s grand.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t appreciate what a fine wife you have. But I don\'92t care. I\'92ll\
get you some place where they can\'92t arrest you and then we\'92ll have a\
lovely time.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s go there right away.\'94\
\
\'93We will, darling. I\'92ll go any place any time you wish.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s not think about anything.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\
