                              CHAPTER XXXV\
\
Catherine went along the lake to the little hotel to see Ferguson and I\
sat in the bar and read the papers. There were comfortable leather\
chairs in the bar and I sat in one of them and read until the barman\
came in. The army had not stood at the Tagliamento. They were falling\
back to the Piave. I remembered the Piave. The railroad crossed it near\
San Dona going up to the front. It was deep and slow there and quite\
narrow. Down below there were mosquito marshes and canals. There were\
some lovely villas. Once, before the war, going up to Cortina D\'92Ampezzo\
I had gone along it for several hours in the hills. Up there it looked\
like a trout stream, flowing swiftly with shallow stretches and pools\
under the shadow of the rocks. The road turned off from it at Cadore. I\
wondered how the army that was up there would come down. The barman came\
in.\
\
\'93Count Greffi was asking for you,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Who?\'94\
\
\'93Count Greffi. You remember the old man who was here when you were here\
before.\'94\
\
\'93Is he here?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he\'92s here with his niece. I told him you were here. He wants you\
to play billiards.\'94\
\
\'93Where is he?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s taking a walk.\'94\
\
\'93How is he?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s younger than ever. He drank three champagne cocktails last night\
before dinner.\'94\
\
\'93How\'92s his billiard game?\'94\
\
\'93Good. He beat me. When I told him you were here he was very pleased.\
There\'92s nobody here for him to play with.\'94\
\
Count Greffi was ninety-four years old. He had been a contemporary of\
Metternich and was an old man with white hair and mustache and beautiful\
manners. He had been in the diplomatic service of both Austria and Italy\
and his birthday parties were the great social event of Milan. He was\
living to be one hundred years old and played a smoothly fluent game of\
billiards that contrasted with his own ninety-four-year-old brittleness.\
I had met him when I had been at Stresa once before out of season and\
while we played billiards we drank champagne. I thought it was a\
splendid custom and he gave me fifteen points in a hundred and beat me.\
\
\'93Why didn\'92t you tell me he was here?\'94\
\
\'93I forgot it.\'94\
\
\'93Who else is here?\'94\
\
\'93No one you know. There are only six people altogether.\'94\
\
\'93What are you doing now?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing.\'94\
\
\'93Come on out fishing.\'94\
\
\'93I could come for an hour.\'94\
\
\'93Come on. Bring the trolling line.\'94\
\
The barman put on a coat and we went out. We went down and got a boat\
and I rowed while the barman sat in the stern and let out the line with\
a spinner and a heavy sinker on the end to troll for lake trout. We\
rowed along the shore, the barman holding the line in his hand and\
giving it occasional jerks forward. Stresa looked very deserted from the\
lake. There were the long rows of bare trees, the big hotels and the\
closed villas. I rowed across to Isola Bella and went close to the\
walls, where the water deepened sharply, and you saw the rock wall\
slanting down in the clear water, and then up and along to the\
fisherman\'92s island. The sun was under a cloud and the water was dark and\
smooth and very cold. We did not have a strike though we saw some\
circles on the water from rising fish.\
\
I rowed up opposite the fisherman\'92s island where there were boats drawn\
up and men were mending nets.\
\
\'93Should we get a drink?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
I brought the boat up to the stone pier and the barman pulled in the\
line, coiling it on the bottom of the boat and hooking the spinner on\
the edge of the gunwale. I stepped out and tied the boat. We went into a\
little caf\'e9, sat at a bare wooden table and ordered vermouth.\
\
\'93Are you tired from rowing?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll row back,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93I like to row.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe if you hold the line it will change the luck.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me how goes the war.\'94\
\
\'93Rotten.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t have to go. I\'92m too old, like Count Greffi.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe you\'92ll have to go yet.\'94\
\
\'93Next year they\'92ll call my class. But I won\'92t go.\'94\
\
\'93What will you do?\'94\
\
\'93Get out of the country. I wouldn\'92t go to war. I was at the war once in\
Abyssinia. Nix. Why do you go?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. I was a fool.\'94\
\
\'93Have another vermouth?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
The barman rowed back. We trolled up the lake beyond Stresa and then\
down not far from shore. I held the taut line and felt the faint pulsing\
of the spinner revolving while I looked at the dark November water of\
the lake and the deserted shore. The barman rowed with long strokes and\
on the forward thrust of the boat the line throbbed. Once I had a\
strike: the line hardened suddenly and jerked back, I pulled and felt\
the live weight of the trout and then the line throbbed again. I had\
missed him.\
\
\'93Did he feel big?\'94\
\
\'93Pretty big.\'94\
\
\'93Once when I was out trolling alone I had the line in my teeth and one\
struck and nearly took my mouth out.\'94\
\
\'93The best way is to have it over your leg,\'94 I said. \'93Then you feel it\
and don\'92t lose your teeth.\'94\
\
I put my hand in the water. It was very cold. We were almost opposite\
the hotel now.\
\
\'93I have to go in,\'94 the barman said, \'93to be there for eleven o\'92clock.\
_L\'92heure du cocktail._\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
I pulled in the line and wrapped it on a stick notched at each end. The\
barman put the boat in a little slip in the stone wall and locked it\
with a chain and padlock.\
\
\'93Any time you want it,\'94 he said, \'93I\'92ll give you the key.\'94\
\
\'93Thanks.\'94\
\
We went up to the hotel and in to the bar. I did not want another drink\
so early in the morning so I went up to our room. The maid had just\
finished doing the room and Catherine was not back yet. I lay down on\
the bed and tried to keep from thinking.\
\
When Catherine came back it was all right again. Ferguson was\
downstairs, she said. She was coming to lunch.\
\
\'93I knew you wouldn\'92t mind,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter, darling?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93I know. You haven\'92t anything to do. All you have is me and I go away.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s true.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry, darling. I know it must be a dreadful feeling to have\
nothing at all suddenly.\'94\
\
\'93My life used to be full of everything,\'94 I said. \'93Now if you aren\'92t with\
me I haven\'92t a thing in the world.\'94\
\
\'93But I\'92ll be with you. I was only gone for two hours. Isn\'92t there\
anything you can do?\'94\
\
\'93I went fishing with the barman.\'94\
\
\'93Wasn\'92t it fun?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t think about me when I\'92m not here.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the way I worked it at the front. But there was something to do\
then.\'94\
\
\'93Othello with his occupation gone,\'94 she teased.\
\
\'93Othello was a nigger,\'94 I said. \'93Besides, I\'92m not jealous. I\'92m just so\
in love with you that there isn\'92t anything else.\'94\
\
\'93Will you be a good boy and be nice to Ferguson?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m always nice to Ferguson unless she curses me.\'94\
\
\'93Be nice to her. Think how much we have and she hasn\'92t anything.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think she wants what we have.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t know much, darling, for such a wise boy.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll be nice to her.\'94\
\
\'93I know you will. You\'92re so sweet.\'94\
\
\'93She won\'92t stay afterward, will she?\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92ll get rid of her.\'94\
\
\'93And then we\'92ll come up here.\'94\
\
\'93Of course. What do you think I want to do?\'94\
\
We went downstairs to have lunch with Ferguson. She was very impressed\
by the hotel and the splendor of the dining-room. We had a good lunch\
with a couple of bottles of white capri. Count Greffi came into the\
dining-room and bowed to us. His niece, who looked a little like my\
grandmother, was with him. I told Catherine and Ferguson about him and\
Ferguson was very impressed. The hotel was very big and grand and empty\
but the food was good, the wine was very pleasant and finally the wine\
made us all feel very well. Catherine had no need to feel any better.\
She was very happy. Ferguson became quite cheerful. I felt very well\
myself. After lunch Ferguson went back to her hotel. She was going to\
lie down for a while after lunch she said.\
\
Along late in the afternoon some one knocked on our door.\
\
\'93Who is it?\'94\
\
\'93The Count Greffi wishes to know if you will play billiards with him.\'94\
\
I looked at my watch; I had taken it off and it was under the pillow.\
\
\'93Do you have to go, darling?\'94 Catherine whispered.\
\
\'93I think I\'92d better.\'94 The watch was a quarter-past four o\'92clock. Out\
loud I said, \'93Tell the Count Greffi I will be in the billiard-room at\
five o\'92clock.\'94\
\
At a quarter to five I kissed Catherine good-by and went into the\
bathroom to dress. Knotting my tie and looking in the glass I looked\
strange to myself in the civilian clothes. I must remember to buy some\
more shirts and socks.\
\
\'93Will you be away a long time?\'94 Catherine asked. She looked lovely in\
the bed. \'93Would you hand me the brush?\'94\
\
I watched her brushing her hair, holding her head so the weight of her\
hair all came on one side. It was dark outside and the light over the\
head of the bed shone on her hair and on her neck and shoulders. I went\
over and kissed her and held her hand with the brush and her head sunk\
back on the pillow. I kissed her neck and shoulders. I felt faint with\
loving her so much.\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to go away.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want you to go away.\'94\
\
\'93I won\'92t go then.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Go. It\'92s only for a little while and then you\'92ll come back.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll have dinner up here.\'94\
\
\'93Hurry and come back.\'94\
\
I found the Count Greffi in the billiard-room. He was practising\
strokes, looking very fragile under the light that came down above the\
billiard table. On a card table a little way beyond the light was a\
silver icing-bucket with the necks and corks of two champagne bottles\
showing above the ice. The Count Greffi straightened up when I came\
toward the table and walked toward me. He put out his hand, \'93It is such\
a great pleasure that you are here. You were very kind to come to play\
with me.\'94\
\
\'93It was very nice of you to ask me.\'94\
\
\'93Are you quite well? They told me you were wounded on the Isonzo. I hope\
you are well again.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m very well. Have you been well?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I am always well. But I am getting old. I detect signs of age now.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t believe it.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Do you want to know one? It is easier for me to talk Italian. I\
discipline myself but I find when I am tired that it is so much easier\
to talk Italian. So I know I must be getting old.\'94\
\
\'93We could talk Italian. I am a little tired too.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, but when you are tired it will be easier for you to talk English.\'94\
\
\'93American.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. American. You will please talk American. It is a delightful\
language.\'94\
\
\'93I hardly ever see Americans.\'94\
\
\'93You must miss them. One misses one\'92s countrymen and especially one\'92s\
countrywomen. I know that experience. Should we play or are you too\
tired?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not really tired. I said that for a joke. What handicap will you\
give me?\'94\
\
\'93Have you been playing very much?\'94\
\
\'93None at all.\'94\
\
\'93You play very well. Ten points in a hundred?\'94\
\
\'93You flatter me.\'94\
\
\'93Fifteen?\'94\
\
\'93That would be fine but you will beat me.\'94\
\
\'93Should we play for a stake? You always wished to play for a stake.\'94\
\
\'93I think we\'92d better.\'94\
\
\'93All right. I will give you eighteen points and we will play for a franc\
a point.\'94\
\
He played a lovely game of billiards and with the handicap I was only\
four ahead at fifty. Count Greffi pushed a button on the wall to ring\
for the barman.\
\
\'93Open one bottle please,\'94 he said. Then to me, \'93We will take a little\
stimulant.\'94 The wine was icy cold and very dry and good.\
\
\'93Should we talk Italian? Would you mind very much? It is my great\
weakness now.\'94\
\
We went on playing, sipping the wine between shots, speaking in Italian,\
but talking little, concentrated on the game. Count Greffi made his one\
hundredth point and with the handicap I was only at ninety-four. He\
smiled and patted me on the shoulder.\
\
\'93Now we will drink the other bottle and you will tell me about the war.\'94\
He waited for me to sit down.\
\
\'93About anything else,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93You don\'92t want to talk about it? Good. What have you been reading?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m afraid I am very dull.\'94\
\
\'93No. But you should read.\'94\
\
\'93What is there written in war-time?\'94\
\
\'93There is \'91Le Feu\'92 by a Frenchman, Barbusse. There is \'91Mr. Britling Sees\
Through It.\'92\'94\
\
\'93No, he doesn\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93What?\'94\
\
\'93He doesn\'92t see through it. Those books were at the hospital.\'94\
\
\'93Then you have been reading?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, but nothing any good.\'94\
\
\'93I thought \'91Mr. Britling\'92 a very good study of the English middle-class\
soul.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know about the soul.\'94\
\
\'93Poor boy. We none of us know about the soul. Are you _Croyant_?\'94\
\
\'93At night.\'94\
\
Count Greffi smiled and turned the glass with his fingers. \'93I had\
expected to become more devout as I grow older but somehow I haven\'92t,\'94\
he said. \'93It is a great pity.\'94\
\
\'93Would you like to live after death?\'94 I asked and instantly felt a fool\
to mention death. But he did not mind the word.\
\
\'93It would depend on the life. This life is very pleasant. I would like\
to live forever,\'94 he smiled. \'93I very nearly have.\'94\
\
We were sitting in the deep leather chairs, the champagne in the\
ice-bucket and our glasses on the table between us.\
\
\'93If you ever live to be as old as I am you will find many things\
strange.\'94\
\
\'93You never seem old.\'94\
\
\'93It is the body that is old. Sometimes I am afraid I will break off a\
finger as one breaks a stick of chalk. And the spirit is no older and\
not much wiser.\'94\
\
\'93You are wise.\'94\
\
\'93No, that is the great fallacy; the wisdom of old men. They do not grow\
wise. They grow careful.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps that is wisdom.\'94\
\
\'93It is a very unattractive wisdom. What do you value most?\'94\
\
\'93Some one I love.\'94\
\
\'93With me it is the same. That is not wisdom. Do you value life?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93So do I. Because it is all I have. And to give birthday parties,\'94 he\
laughed. \'93You are probably wiser than I am. You do not give birthday\
parties.\'94\
\
We both drank the wine.\
\
\'93What do you think of the war really?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93I think it is stupid.\'94\
\
\'93Who will win it?\'94\
\
\'93Italy.\'94\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93They are a younger nation.\'94\
\
\'93Do younger nations always win wars?\'94\
\
\'93They are apt to for a time.\'94\
\
\'93Then what happens?\'94\
\
\'93They become older nations.\'94\
\
\'93You said you were not wise.\'94\
\
\'93Dear boy, that is not wisdom. That is cynicism.\'94\
\
\'93It sounds very wise to me.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s not particularly. I could quote you the examples on the other\
side. But it is not bad. Have we finished the champagne?\'94\
\
\'93Almost.\'94\
\
\'93Should we drink some more? Then I must dress.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps we\'92d better not now.\'94\
\
\'93You are sure you don\'92t want more?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94 He stood up.\
\
\'93I hope you will be very fortunate and very happy and very, very\
healthy.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you. And I hope you will live forever.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you. I have. And if you ever become devout pray for me if I am\
dead. I am asking several of my friends to do that. I had expected to\
become devout myself but it has not come.\'94 I thought he smiled sadly but\
I could not tell. He was so old and his face was very wrinkled, so that\
a smile used so many lines that all gradations were lost.\
\
\'93I might become very devout,\'94 I said. \'93Anyway, I will pray for you.\'94\
\
\'93I had always expected to become devout. All my family died very devout.\
But somehow it does not come.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s too early.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe it is too late. Perhaps I have outlived my religious feeling.\'94\
\
\'93My own comes only at night.\'94\
\
\'93Then too you are in love. Do not forget that is a religious feeling.\'94\
\
\'93You believe so?\'94\
\
\'93Of course.\'94 He took a step toward the table. \'93You were very kind to\
play.\'94\
\
\'93It was a great pleasure.\'94\
\
\'93We will walk upstairs together.\'94\
\
\
\
\
                             CHAPTER XXXVI\
\
That night there was a storm and I woke to hear the rain lashing the\
window-panes. It was coming in the open window. Some one had knocked on\
the door. I went to the door very softly, not to disturb Catherine, and\
opened it. The barman stood there. He wore his overcoat and carried his\
wet hat.\
\
\'93Can I speak to you, Tenente?\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a very serious matter.\'94\
\
I looked around. The room was dark. I saw the water on the floor from\
the window. \'93Come in,\'94 I said. I took him by the arm into the bathroom;\
locked the door and put on the light. I sat down on the edge of the\
bathtub.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter, Emilio? Are you in trouble?\'94\
\
\'93No. You are, Tenente.\'94\
\
\'93Yes?\'94\
\
\'93They are going to arrest you in the morning.\'94\
\
\'93Yes?\'94\
\
\'93I came to tell you. I was out in the town and I heard them talking in a\
caf\'e9.\'94\
\
\'93I see.\'94\
\
He stood there, his coat wet, holding his wet hat and said nothing.\
\
\'93Why are they going to arrest me?\'94\
\
\'93For something about the war.\'94\
\
\'93Do you know what?\'94\
\
\'93No. But I know that they know you were here before as an officer and\
now you are here out of uniform. After this retreat they arrest\
everybody.\'94\
\
I thought a minute.\
\
\'93What time do they come to arrest me?\'94\
\
\'93In the morning. I don\'92t know the time.\'94\
\
\'93What do you say to do?\'94\
\
He put his hat in the washbowl. It was very wet and had been dripping on\
the floor.\
\
\'93If you have nothing to fear an arrest is nothing. But it is always bad\
to be arrested\'97especially now.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to be arrested.\'94\
\
\'93Then go to Switzerland.\'94\
\
\'93How?\'94\
\
\'93In my boat.\'94\
\
\'93There is a storm,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93The storm is over. It is rough but you will be all right.\'94\
\
\'93When should we go?\'94\
\
\'93Right away. They might come to arrest you early in the morning.\'94\
\
\'93What about our bags?\'94\
\
\'93Get them packed. Get your lady dressed. I will take care of them.\'94\
\
\'93Where will you be?\'94\
\
\'93I will wait here. I don\'92t want any one to see me outside in the hall.\'94\
\
I opened the door, closed it, and went into the bedroom. Catherine was\
awake.\
\
\'93What is it, darling?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all right, Cat,\'94 I said. \'93Would you like to get dressed right away\
and go in a boat to Switzerland?\'94\
\
\'93Would you?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92d like to go back to bed.\'94\
\
\'93What is it about?\'94\
\
\'93The barman says they are going to arrest me in the morning.\'94\
\
\'93Is the barman crazy?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Then please hurry, darling, and get dressed so we can start.\'94 She sat\
up on the side of the bed. She was still sleepy. \'93Is that the barman in\
the bathroom?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Then I won\'92t wash. Please look the other way, darling, and I\'92ll be\
dressed in just a minute.\'94\
\
I saw her white back as she took off her nightgown and then I looked\
away because she wanted me to. She was beginning to be a little big with\
the child and she did not want me to see her. I dressed hearing the rain\
on the windows. I did not have much to put in my bag.\
\
\'93There\'92s plenty of room in my bag, Cat, if you need any.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m almost packed,\'94 she said. \'93Darling, I\'92m awfully stupid, but why is\
the barman in the bathroom?\'94\
\
\'93Sh\'97he\'92s waiting to take our bags down.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s awfully nice.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s an old friend,\'94 I said. \'93I nearly sent him some pipe-tobacco\
once.\'94\
\
I looked out the open window at the dark night. I could not see the\
lake, only the dark and the rain but the wind was quieter.\
\
\'93I\'92m ready, darling,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93All right.\'94 I went to the bathroom door. \'93Here are the bags, Emilio,\'94 I\
said. The barman took the two bags.\
\
\'93You\'92re very good to help us,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93That\'92s nothing, lady,\'94 the barman said. \'93I\'92m glad to help you just so I\
don\'92t get in trouble myself. Listen,\'94 he said to me. \'93I\'92ll take these\
out the servants\'92 stairs and to the boat. You just go out as though you\
were going for a walk.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lovely night for a walk,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93It\'92s a bad night all right.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m glad I\'92ve an umbrella,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
We walked down the hall and down the wide thickly carpeted stairs. At\
the foot of the stairs by the door the porter sat behind his desk.\
\
He looked surprised at seeing us.\
\
\'93You\'92re not going out, sir?\'94 he said.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93We\'92re going to see the storm along the lake.\'94\
\
\'93Haven\'92t you got an umbrella, sir?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93This coat sheds water.\'94\
\
He looked at it doubtfully. \'93I\'92ll get you an umbrella, sir,\'94 he said. He\
went away and came back with a big umbrella. \'93It is a little big, sir,\'94\
he said. I gave him a ten-lira note. \'93Oh you are too good, sir. Thank\
you very much,\'94 he said. He held the door open and we went out into the\
rain. He smiled at Catherine and she smiled at him. \'93Don\'92t stay out in\
the storm,\'94 he said. \'93You will get wet, sir and lady.\'94 He was only the\
second porter, and his English was still literally translated.\
\
\'93We\'92ll be back,\'94 I said. We walked down the path under the giant\
umbrella and out through the dark wet gardens to the road and across the\
road to the trellised pathway along the lake. The wind was blowing\
offshore now. It was a cold, wet November wind and I knew it was snowing\
in the mountains. We came along past the chained boats in the slips\
along the quay to where the barman\'92s boat should be. The water was dark\
against the stone. The barman stepped out from beside the row of trees.\
\
\'93The bags are in the boat,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93I want to pay you for the boat,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93How much money have you?\'94\
\
\'93Not so much.\'94\
\
\'93You send me the money later. That will be all right.\'94\
\
\'93How much?\'94\
\
\'93What you want.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me how much.\'94\
\
\'93If you get through send me five hundred francs. You won\'92t mind that if\
you get through.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Here are sandwiches.\'94 He handed me a package. \'93Everything there was in\
the bar. It\'92s all here. This is a bottle of brandy and a bottle of\
wine.\'94 I put them in my bag. \'93Let me pay you for those.\'94\
\
\'93All right, give me fifty lire.\'94\
\
I gave it to him. \'93The brandy is good,\'94 he said. \'93You don\'92t need to be\
afraid to give it to your lady. She better get in the boat.\'94 He held the\
boat, it rising and falling against the stone wall and I helped\
Catherine in. She sat in the stern and pulled her cape around her.\
\
\'93You know where to go?\'94\
\
\'93Up the lake.\'94\
\
\'93You know how far?\'94\
\
\'93Past Luino.\'94\
\
\'93Past Luino, Cannero, Cannobio, Tranzano. You aren\'92t in Switzerland\
until you come to Brissago. You have to pass Monte Tamara.\'94\
\
\'93What time is it?\'94 Catherine asked.\
\
\'93It\'92s only eleven o\'92clock,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93If you row all the time you ought to be there by seven o\'92clock in the\
morning.\'94\
\
\'93Is it that far?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s thirty-five kilometres.\'94\
\
\'93How should we go? In this rain we need a compass.\'94\
\
\'93No. Row to Isola Bella. Then on the other side of Isola Madre go with\
the wind. The wind will take you to Pallanza. You will see the lights.\
Then go up the shore.\'94\
\
\'93Maybe the wind will change.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 he said. \'93This wind will blow like this for three days. It comes\
straight down from the Mattarone. There is a can to bail with.\'94\
\
\'93Let me pay you something for the boat now.\'94\
\
\'93No, I\'92d rather take a chance. If you get through you pay me all you\
can.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think you\'92ll get drowned.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s good.\'94\
\
\'93Go with the wind up the lake.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94 I stepped in the boat.\
\
\'93Did you leave the money for the hotel?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. In an envelope in the room.\'94\
\
\'93All right. Good luck, Tenente.\'94\
\
\'93Good luck. We thank you many times.\'94\
\
\'93You won\'92t thank me if you get drowned.\'94\
\
\'93What does he say?\'94 Catherine asked.\
\
\'93He says good luck.\'94\
\
\'93Good luck,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Thank you very much.\'94\
\
\'93Are you ready?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
He bent down and shoved us off. I dug at the water with the oars, then\
waved one hand. The barman waved back deprecatingly. I saw the lights of\
the hotel and rowed out, rowing straight out until they were out of\
sight. There was quite a sea running but we were going with the wind.\
\
\
\
\
                             CHAPTER XXXVII\
\
I rowed in the dark keeping the wind in my face. The rain had stopped\
and only came occasionally in gusts. It was very dark, and the wind was\
cold. I could see Catherine in the stern but I could not see the water\
where the blades of the oars dipped. The oars were long and there were\
no leathers to keep them from slipping out. I pulled, raised, leaned\
forward, found the water, dipped and pulled, rowing as easily as I\
could. I did not feather the oars because the wind was with us. I knew\
my hands would blister and I wanted to delay it as long as I could. The\
boat was light and rowed easily. I pulled it along in the dark water. I\
could not see, and hoped we would soon come opposite Pallanza.\
\
We never saw Pallanza. The wind was blowing up the lake and we passed\
the point that hides Pallanza in the dark and never saw the lights. When\
we finally saw some lights much further up the lake and close to the\
shore it was Intra. But for a long time we did not see any lights, nor\
did we see the shore but rowed steadily in the dark riding with the\
waves. Sometimes I missed the water with the oars in the dark as a wave\
lifted the boat. It was quite rough; but I kept on rowing, until\
suddenly we were close ashore against a point of rock that rose beside\
us; the waves striking against it, rushing high up, then falling back. I\
pulled hard on the right oar and backed water with the other and we went\
out into the lake again; the point was out of sight and we were going on\
up the lake.\
\
\'93We\'92re across the lake,\'94 I said to Catherine.\
\
\'93Weren\'92t we going to see Pallanza?\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ve missed it.\'94\
\
\'93How are you, darling?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m fine.\'94\
\
\'93I could take the oars awhile.\'94\
\
\'93No, I\'92m fine.\'94\
\
\'93Poor Ferguson,\'94 Catherine said. \'93In the morning she\'92ll come to the\
hotel and find we\'92re gone.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not worrying so much about that,\'94 I said, \'93as about getting into\
the Swiss part of the lake before it\'92s daylight and the custom guards\
see us.\'94\
\
\'93Is it a long way?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s thirty some kilometres from here.\'94\
\
\
\
I rowed all night. Finally my hands were so sore I could hardly close\
them over the oars. We were nearly smashed up on the shore several\
times. I kept fairly close to the shore because I was afraid of getting\
lost on the lake and losing time. Sometimes we were so close we could\
see a row of trees and the road along the shore with the mountains\
behind. The rain stopped and the wind drove the clouds so that the moon\
shone through and looking back I could see the long dark point of\
Castagnola and the lake with white-caps and beyond, the moon on the high\
snow mountains. Then the clouds came over the moon again and the\
mountains and the lake were gone, but it was much lighter than it had\
been before and we could see the shore. I could see it too clearly and\
pulled out where they would not see the boat if there were custom guards\
along the Pallanza road. When the moon came out again we could see white\
villas on the shore on the slopes of the mountain and the white road\
where it showed through the trees. All the time I was rowing.\
\
The lake widened and across it on the shore at the foot of the mountains\
on the other side we saw a few lights that should be Luino. I saw a\
wedgelike gap between the mountains on the other shore and I thought\
that must be Luino. If it was we were making good time. I pulled in the\
oars and lay back on the seat. I was very, very tired of rowing. My arms\
and shoulders and back ached and my hands were sore.\
\
\'93I could hold the umbrella,\'94 Catherine said. \'93We could sail with that\
with the wind.\'94\
\
\'93Can you steer?\'94\
\
\'93I think so.\'94\
\
\'93You take this oar and hold it under your arm close to the side of the\
boat and steer and I\'92ll hold the umbrella.\'94 I went back to the stern and\
showed her how to hold the oar. I took the big umbrella the porter had\
given me and sat facing the bow and opened it. It opened with a clap. I\
held it on both sides, sitting astride the handle hooked over the seat.\
The wind was full in it and I felt the boat suck forward while I held as\
hard as I could to the two edges. It pulled hard. The boat was moving\
fast.\
\
\'93We\'92re going beautifully,\'94 Catherine said. All I could see was umbrella\
ribs. The umbrella strained and pulled and I felt us driving along with\
it. I braced my feet and held back on it, then suddenly, it buckled; I\
felt a rib snap on my forehead, I tried to grab the top that was bending\
with the wind and the whole thing buckled and went inside-out and I was\
astride the handle of an inside-out, ripped umbrella, where I had been\
holding a wind-filled pulling sail. I unhooked the handle from the seat,\
laid the umbrella in the bow and went back to Catherine for the oar. She\
was laughing. She took my hand and kept on laughing.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 I took the oar.\
\
\'93You looked so funny holding that thing.\'94\
\
\'93I suppose so.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be cross, darling. It was awfully funny. You looked about twenty\
feet broad and very affectionate holding the umbrella by the edges\'97\'94\
she choked.\
\
\'93I\'92ll row.\'94\
\
\'93Take a rest and a drink. It\'92s a grand night and we\'92ve come a long way.\'94\
\
\'93I have to keep the boat out of the trough of the waves.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll get you a drink. Then rest a little while, darling.\'94\
\
I held the oars up and we sailed with them. Catherine was opening the\
bag. She handed me the brandy bottle. I pulled the cork with my\
pocket-knife and took a long drink. It was smooth and hot and the heat\
went all through me and I felt warmed and cheerful. \'93It\'92s lovely\
brandy,\'94 I said. The moon was under again but I could see the shore.\
There seemed to be another point going out a long way ahead into the\
lake.\
\
\'93Are you warm enough, Cat?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m splendid. I\'92m a little stiff.\'94\
\
\'93Bail out that water and you can put your feet down.\'94\
\
Then I rowed and listened to the oarlocks and the dip and scrape of the\
bailing tin under the stern seat.\
\
\'93Would you give me the bailer?\'94 I said. \'93I want a drink.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s awfully dirty.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s all right. I\'92ll rinse it.\'94\
\
I heard Catherine rinsing it over the side. Then she handed it to me\
dipped full of water. I was thirsty after the brandy and the water was\
icy cold, so cold it made my teeth ache. I looked toward the shore. We\
were closer to the long point. There were lights in the bay ahead.\
\
\'93Thanks,\'94 I said and handed back the tin pail.\
\
\'93You\'92re ever so welcome,\'94 Catherine said. \'93There\'92s much more if you want\
it.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want to eat something?\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92ll be hungry in a little while. We\'92ll save it till then.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
What looked like a point ahead was a long high headland. I went further\
out in the lake to pass it. The lake was much narrower now. The moon was\
out again and the _guardia di Finanza_ could have seen our boat black on\
the water if they had been watching.\
\
\'93How are you, Cat?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93I\'92m all right. Where are we?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think we have more than about eight miles more.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s a long way to row, you poor sweet. Aren\'92t you dead?\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92m all right. My hands are sore is all.\'94\
\
We went on up the lake. There was a break in the mountains on the right\
bank, a flattening-out with a low shore-line that I thought must be\
Cannobio. I stayed a long way out because it was from now on that we ran\
the most danger of meeting _guardia_. There was a high dome-capped\
mountain on the other shore a way ahead. I was tired. It was no great\
distance to row but when you were out of condition it had been a long\
way. I knew I had to pass that mountain and go up the lake at least five\
miles further before we would be in Swiss water. The moon was almost\
down now but before it went down the sky clouded over again and it was\
very dark. I stayed well out in the lake, rowing awhile, then resting\
and holding the oars so that the wind struck the blades.\
\
\'93Let me row awhile,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93I don\'92t think you ought to.\'94\
\
\'93Nonsense. It would be good for me. It would keep me from being too\
stiff.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think you should, Cat.\'94\
\
\'93Nonsense. Rowing in moderation is very good for the pregnant lady.\'94\
\
\'93All right, you row a little moderately. I\'92ll go back, then you come up.\
Hold on to both gunwales when you come up.\'94\
\
I sat in the stern with my coat on and the collar turned up and watched\
Catherine row. She rowed very well but the oars were too long and\
bothered her. I opened the bag and ate a couple of sandwiches and took a\
drink of the brandy. It made everything much better and I took another\
drink.\
\
\'93Tell me when you\'92re tired,\'94 I said. Then a little later, \'93watch out the\
oar doesn\'92t pop you in the tummy.\'94\
\
\'93If it did\'94\'97Catherine said between strokes\'97\'93life might be much\
simpler.\'94\
\
I took another drink of the brandy.\
\
\'93How are you going?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93Tell me when you want to stop.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
I took another drink of the brandy, then took hold of the two gunwales\
of the boat and moved forward.\
\
\'93No. I\'92m going beautifully.\'94\
\
\'93Go on back to the stern. I\'92ve had a grand rest.\'94\
\
For a while, with the brandy, I rowed easily and steadily. Then I began\
to catch crabs and soon I was just chopping along again with a thin\
brown taste of bile from having rowed too hard after the brandy.\
\
\'93Give me a drink of water, will you?\'94 I said.\
\
\'93That\'92s easy,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
Before daylight it started to drizzle. The wind was down or we were\
protected by mountains that bounded the curve the lake had made. When I\
knew daylight was coming I settled down and rowed hard. I did not know\
where we were and I wanted to get into the Swiss part of the lake. When\
it was beginning to be daylight we were quite close to the shore. I\
could see the rocky shore and the trees.\
\
\'93What\'92s that?\'94 Catherine said. I rested on the oars and listened. It was\
a motor boat chugging out on the lake. I pulled close up to the shore\
and lay quiet. The chugging came closer; then we saw the motor boat in\
the rain a little astern of us. There were four _guardia_ _di finanza_\
in the stern, their _alpini_ hats pulled down, their cape collars turned\
up and their carbines slung across their backs. They all looked sleepy\
so early in the morning. I could see the yellow on their hats and the\
yellow marks on their cape collars. The motor boat chugged on and out of\
sight in the rain.\
\
I pulled out into the lake. If we were that close to the border I did\
not want to be hailed by a sentry along the road. I stayed out where I\
could just see the shore and rowed on for three-quarters of an hour in\
the rain. We heard a motor boat once more but I kept quiet until the\
noise of the engine went away across the lake.\
\
\'93I think we\'92re in Switzerland, Cat,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Really?\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no way to know until we see Swiss troops.\'94\
\
\'93Or the Swiss navy.\'94\
\
\'93The Swiss navy\'92s no joke for us. That last motor boat we heard was\
probably the Swiss navy.\'94\
\
\'93If we\'92re in Switzerland let\'92s have a big breakfast. They have wonderful\
rolls and butter and jam in Switzerland.\'94\
\
\
\
It was clear daylight now and a fine rain was falling. The wind was\
still blowing outside up the lake and we could see the tops of the\
white-caps going away from us and up the lake. I was sure we were in\
Switzerland now. There were many houses back in the trees from the shore\
and up the shore a way was a village with stone houses, some villas on\
the hills and a church. I had been looking at the road that skirted the\
shore for guards but did not see any. The road came quite close to the\
lake now and I saw a soldier coming out of a caf\'e9 on the road. He wore a\
gray-green uniform and a helmet like the Germans. He had a\
healthy-looking face and a little toothbrush mustache. He looked at us.\
\
\'93Wave to him,\'94 I said to Catherine. She waved and the soldier smiled\
embarrassedly and gave a wave of his hand. I eased up rowing. We were\
passing the waterfront of the village.\
\
\'93We must be well inside the border,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We want to be sure, darling. We don\'92t want them to turn us back at the\
frontier.\'94\
\
\'93The frontier is a long way back. I think this is the customs town. I\'92m\
pretty sure it\'92s Brissago.\'94\
\
\'93Won\'92t there be Italians there? There are always both sides at a customs\
town.\'94\
\
\'93Not in war-time. I don\'92t think they let the Italians cross the\
frontier.\'94\
\
It was a nice-looking little town. There were many fishing boats along\
the quay and nets were spread on racks. There was a fine November rain\
falling but it looked cheerful and clean even with the rain.\
\
\'93Should we land then and have breakfast?\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
I pulled hard on the left oar and came in close, then straightened out\
when we were close to the quay and brought the boat alongside. I pulled\
in the oars, took hold of an iron ring, stepped up on the wet stone and\
was in Switzerland. I tied the boat and held my hand down to Catherine.\
\
\'93Come on up, Cat. It\'92s a grand feeling.\'94\
\
\'93What about the bags?\'94\
\
\'93Leave them in the boat.\'94\
\
Catherine stepped up and we were in Switzerland together.\
\
\'93What a lovely country,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93Isn\'92t it grand?\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s go and have breakfast!\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t it a grand country? I love the way it feels under my shoes.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m so stiff I can\'92t feel it very well. But it feels like a splendid\
country. Darling, do you realize we\'92re here and out of that bloody\
place?\'94\
\
\'93I do. I really do. I\'92ve never realized anything before.\'94\
\
\'93Look at the houses. Isn\'92t this a fine square? There\'92s a place we can\
get breakfast.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t the rain fine? They never had rain like this in Italy. It\'92s\
cheerful rain.\'94\
\
\'93And we\'92re here, darling! Do you realize we\'92re here?\'94\
\
We went inside the caf\'e9 and sat down at a clean wooden table. We were\
cockeyed excited. A splendid clean-looking woman with an apron came and\
asked us what we wanted.\
\
\'93Rolls and jam and coffee,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry, we haven\'92t any rolls in war-time.\'94\
\
\'93Bread then.\'94\
\
\'93I can make you some toast.\'94\
\
\'93All right.\'94\
\
\'93I want some eggs fried too.\'94\
\
\'93How many eggs for the gentleman?\'94\
\
\'93Three.\'94\
\
\'93Take four, darling.\'94\
\
\'93Four eggs.\'94\
\
The woman went away. I kissed Catherine and held her hand very tight. We\
looked at each other and at the caf\'e9.\
\
\'93Darling, darling, isn\'92t it lovely?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s grand,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I don\'92t mind there not being rolls,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I thought about\
them all night. But I don\'92t mind it. I don\'92t mind it at all.\'94\
\
\'93I suppose pretty soon they will arrest us.\'94\
\
\'93Never mind, darling. We\'92ll have breakfast first. You won\'92t mind being\
arrested after breakfast. And then there\'92s nothing they can do to us.\
We\'92re British and American citizens in good standing.\'94\
\
\'93You have a passport, haven\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93Of course. Oh let\'92s not talk about it. Let\'92s be happy.\'94\
\
\'93I couldn\'92t be any happier,\'94 I said. A fat gray cat with a tail that\
lifted like a plume crossed the floor to our table and curved against my\
leg to purr each time she rubbed. I reached down and stroked her.\
Catherine smiled at me very happily. \'93Here comes the coffee,\'94 she said.\
\
\
\
They arrested us after breakfast. We took a little walk through the\
village then went down to the quay to get our bags. A soldier was\
standing guard over the boat.\
\
\'93Is this your boat?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Where do you come from?\'94\
\
\'93Up the lake.\'94\
\
\'93Then I have to ask you to come with me.\'94\
\
\'93How about the bags?\'94\
\
\'93You can carry the bags.\'94\
\
I carried the bags and Catherine walked beside me and the soldier walked\
along behind us to the old custom house. In the custom house a\
lieutenant, very thin and military, questioned us.\
\
\'93What nationality are you?\'94\
\
\'93American and British.\'94\
\
\'93Let me see your passports.\'94\
\
I gave him mine and Catherine got hers out of her handbag.\
\
He examined them for a long time.\
\
\'93Why do you enter Switzerland this way in a boat?\'94\
\
\'93I am a sportsman,\'94 I said. \'93Rowing is my great sport. I always row when\
I get a chance.\'94\
\
\'93Why do you come here?\'94\
\
\'93For the winter sport. We are tourists and we want to do the winter\
sport.\'94\
\
\'93This is no place for winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93We know it. We want to go where they have the winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93What have you been doing in Italy?\'94\
\
\'93I have been studying architecture. My cousin has been studying art.\'94\
\
\'93Why do you leave there?\'94\
\
\'93We want to do the winter sport. With the war going on you cannot study\
architecture.\'94\
\
\'93You will please stay where you are,\'94 the lieutenant said. He went back\
into the building with our passports.\
\
\'93You\'92re splendid, darling,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Keep on the same track. You\
want to do the winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93Do you know anything about art?\'94\
\
\'93Rubens,\'94 said Catherine.\
\
\'93Large and fat,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Titian,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93Titian-haired,\'94 I said. \'93How about Mantegna?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t ask hard ones,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I know him though\'97very bitter.\'94\
\
\'93Very bitter,\'94 I said. \'93Lots of nail holes.\'94\
\
\'93You see I\'92ll make you a fine wife,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I\'92ll be able to\
talk art with your customers.\'94\
\
\'93Here he comes,\'94 I said. The thin lieutenant came down the length of the\
custom house, holding our passports.\
\
\'93I will have to send you into Locarno,\'94 he said. \'93You can get a carriage\
and a soldier will go in with you.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said. \'93What about the boat?\'94\
\
\'93The boat is confiscated. What have you in those bags?\'94\
\
He went all through the two bags and held up the quarter-bottle of\
brandy. \'93Would you join me in a drink?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93No thank you.\'94 He straightened up. \'93How much money have you?\'94\
\
\'93Twenty-five hundred lire.\'94\
\
He was favorably impressed. \'93How much has your cousin?\'94\
\
Catherine had a little over twelve hundred lire. The lieutenant was\
pleased. His attitude toward us became less haughty.\
\
\'93If you are going for winter sports,\'94 he said, \'93Wengen is the place. My\
father has a very fine hotel at Wengen. It is open all the time.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s splendid,\'94 I said. \'93Could you give me the name?\'94\
\
\'93I will write it on a card.\'94 He handed me the card very politely.\
\
\'93The soldier will take you in to Locarno. He will keep your passports. I\
regret this but it is necessary. I have good hopes they will give you a\
visa or a police permit at Locarno.\'94\
\
He handed the two passports to the soldier and carrying the bags we\
started into the village to order a carriage. \'93Hi,\'94 the lieutenant\
called to the soldier. He said something in a German dialect to him. The\
soldier slung his rifle on his back and picked up the bags.\
\
\'93It\'92s a great country,\'94 I said to Catherine.\
\
\'93It\'92s so practical.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you very much,\'94 I said to the lieutenant. He waved his hand.\
\
_\'93Service!_\'94 he said. We followed our guard into the village.\
\
We drove to Locarno in a carriage with the soldier sitting on the front\
seat with the driver. At Locarno we did not have a bad time. They\
questioned us but they were polite because we had passports and money. I\
do not think they believed a word of the story and I thought it was\
silly but it was like a law-court. You did not want something\
reasonable, you wanted something technical and then stuck to it without\
explanations. But we had passports and we would spend the money. So they\
gave us provisional visas. At any time this visa might be withdrawn. We\
were to report to the police wherever we went.\
\
Could we go wherever we wanted? Yes. Where did we want to go?\
\
\'93Where do you want to go, Cat?\'94\
\
\'93Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93It is a very nice place,\'94 the official said. \'93I think you will like\
that place.\'94\
\
\'93Here at Locarno is a very nice place,\'94 another official said. \'93I am\
sure you would like it here very much at Locarno. Locarno is a very\
attractive place.\'94\
\
\'93We would like some place where there is winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93There is no winter sport at Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93I beg your pardon,\'94 the other official said. \'93I come from Montreux.\
There is very certainly winter sport on the Montreux Oberland Bernois\
railway. It would be false for you to deny that.\'94\
\
\'93I do not deny it. I simply said there is no winter sport at Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93I question that,\'94 the other official said. \'93I question that statement.\'94\
\
\'93I hold to that statement.\'94\
\
\'93I question that statement. I myself have _luge-ed_ into the streets of\
Montreux. I have done it not once but several times. Luge-ing is\
certainly winter sport.\'94\
\
The other official turned to me.\
\
\'93Is luge-ing your idea of winter sport, sir? I tell you you would be\
very comfortable here in Locarno. You would find the climate healthy,\
you would find the environs attractive. You would like it very much.\'94\
\
\'93The gentleman has expressed a wish to go to Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93What is luge-ing?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93You see he has never even heard of luge-ing!\'94\
\
That meant a great deal to the second official. He was pleased by that.\
\
\'93Luge-ing,\'94 said the first official, \'93is tobogganing.\'94\
\
\'93I beg to differ,\'94 the other official shook his head. \'93I must differ\
again. The toboggan is very different from the luge. The toboggan is\
constructed in Canada of flat laths. The luge is a common sled with\
runners. Accuracy means something.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t we toboggan?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Of course you could toboggan,\'94 the first official said. \'93You could\
toboggan very well. Excellent Canadian toboggans are sold in Montreux.\
Ochs Brothers sell toboggans. They import their own toboggans.\'94\
\
The second official turned away. \'93Tobogganing,\'94 he said, \'93requires a\
special _piste_. You could not toboggan into the streets of Montreux.\
Where are you stopping here?\'94\
\
\'93We don\'92t know,\'94 I said. \'93We just drove in from Brissago. The carriage\
is outside.\'94\
\
\'93You make no mistake in going to Montreux,\'94 the first official said.\
\'93You will find the climate delightful and beautiful. You will have no\
distance to go for winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93If you really want winter sport,\'94 the second official said, \'93you will\
go to the Engadine or to M\'fcrren. I must protest against your being\
advised to go to Montreux for the winter sport.\'94\
\
\'93At Les Avants above Montreux there is excellent winter sport of every\
sort.\'94 The champion of Montreux glared at his colleague.\
\
\'93Gentlemen,\'94 I said, \'93I am afraid we must go. My cousin is very tired.\
We will go tentatively to Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93I congratulate you,\'94 the first official shook my hand.\
\
\'93I believe that you will regret leaving Locarno,\'94 the second official\
said. \'93At any rate you will report to the police at Montreux.\'94\
\
\'93There will be no unpleasantness with the police,\'94 the first official\
assured me. \'93You will find all the inhabitants extremely courteous and\
friendly.\'94\
\
\'93Thank you both very much,\'94 I said. \'93We appreciate your advice very\
much.\'94\
\
\'93Good-by,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Thank you both very much.\'94\
\
They bowed us to the door, the champion of Locarno a little coldly. We\
went down the steps and into the carriage.\
\
\'93My God, darling,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Couldn\'92t we have gotten away any\
sooner?\'94 I gave the name of a hotel one of the officials had recommended\
to the driver. He picked up the reins.\
\
\'93You\'92ve forgotten the army,\'94 Catherine said. The soldier was standing by\
the carriage. I gave him a ten-lira note. \'93I have no Swiss money yet,\'94 I\
said. He thanked me, saluted and went off. The carriage started and we\
drove to the hotel.\
\
\'93How did you happen to pick out Montreux?\'94 I asked Catherine. \'93Do you\
really want to go there?\'94\
\
\'93It was the first place I could think of,\'94 she said. \'93It\'92s not a bad\
place. We can find some place up in the mountains.\'94\
\
\'93Are you sleepy?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m asleep right now.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll get a good sleep. Poor Cat, you had a long bad night.\'94\
\
\'93I had a lovely time,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Especially when you sailed with\
the umbrella.\'94\
\
\'93Can you realize we\'92re in Switzerland?\'94\
\
\'93No, I\'92m afraid I\'92ll wake up and it won\'92t be true.\'94\
\
\'93I am too.\'94\
\
\'93It is true, isn\'92t it, darling? I\'92m not just driving down to the\
_stazione_ in Milan to see you off.\'94\
\
\'93I hope not.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t say that. It frightens me. Maybe that\'92s where we\'92re going.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m so groggy I don\'92t know,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Let me see your hands.\'94\
\
I put them out. They were both blistered raw.\
\
\'93There\'92s no hole in my side,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t be sacrilegious.\'94\
\
I felt very tired and vague in the head. The exhilaration was all gone.\
The carriage was going along the street.\
\
\'93Poor hands,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t touch them,\'94 I said. \'93By God I don\'92t know where we are. Where are\
we going, driver?\'94 The driver stopped his horse.\
\
\'93To the Hotel Metropole. Don\'92t you want to go there?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s all right, Cat.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all right, darling. Don\'92t be upset. We\'92ll get a good sleep and you\
won\'92t feel groggy to-morrow.\'94\
\
\'93I get pretty groggy,\'94 I said. \'93It\'92s like a comic opera to-day. Maybe\
I\'92m hungry.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re just tired, darling. You\'92ll be fine.\'94 The carriage pulled up\
before the hotel. Some one came out to take our bags.\
\
\'93I feel all right,\'94 I said. We were down on the pavement going into the\
hotel.\
\
\'93I know you\'92ll be all right. You\'92re just tired. You\'92ve been up a long\
time.\'94\
\
\'93Anyhow we\'92re here.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, we\'92re really here.\'94\
\
We followed the boy with the bags into the hotel.\
