\
\
\
\
                             CHAPTER XXXIX\
\
By the middle of January I had a beard and the winter had settled into\
bright cold days and hard cold nights. We could walk on the roads again.\
The snow was packed hard and smooth by the hay-sleds and wood-sledges\
and the logs that were hauled down the mountain. The snow lay over all\
the country, down almost to Montreux. The mountains on the other side of\
the lake were all white and the plain of the Rhone valley was covered.\
We took long walks on the other side of the mountain to the Bains de\
l\'92Alliaz. Catherine wore hobnailed boots and a cape and carried a stick\
with a sharp steel point. She did not look big with the cape and we\
would not walk too fast but stopped and sat on logs by the roadside to\
rest when she was tired.\
\
There was an inn in the trees at the Bains de l\'92Alliaz where the\
woodcutters stopped to drink, and we sat inside warmed by the stove and\
drank hot red wine with spices and lemon in it. They called it\
_gl\'fchwein_ and it was a good thing to warm you and to celebrate with.\
The inn was dark and smoky inside and afterward when you went out the\
cold air came sharply into your lungs and numbed the edge of your nose\
as you inhaled. We looked back at the inn with light coming from the\
windows and the woodcutters\'92 horses stamping and jerking their heads\
outside to keep warm. There was frost on the hairs of their muzzles and\
their breathing made plumes of frost in the air. Going up the road\
toward home the road was smooth and slippery for a while and the ice\
orange from the horses until the wood-hauling track turned off. Then the\
road was clean-packed snow and led through the woods, and twice coming\
home in the evening, we saw foxes.\
\
It was a fine country and every time that we went out it was fun.\
\
\'93You have a splendid beard now,\'94 Catherine said. \'93It looks just like the\
woodcutters\'92. Did you see the man with the tiny gold ear-rings?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s a chamois hunter,\'94 I said. \'93They wear them because they say it\
makes them hear better.\'94\
\
\'93Really? I don\'92t believe it. I think they wear them to show they are\
chamois hunters. Are there chamois near here?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, beyond the Dent de Jaman.\'94\
\
\'93It was fun seeing the fox.\'94\
\
\'93When he sleeps he wraps that tail around him to keep warm.\'94\
\
\'93It must be a lovely feeling.\'94\
\
\'93I always wanted to have a tail like that. Wouldn\'92t it be fun if we had\
brushes like a fox?\'94\
\
\'93It might be very difficult dressing.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92d have clothes made, or live in a country where it wouldn\'92t make any\
difference.\'94\
\
\'93We live in a country where nothing makes any difference. Isn\'92t it grand\
how we never see any one? You don\'92t want to see people do you, darling?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93Should we sit here just a minute? I\'92m a little bit tired.\'94\
\
We sat close together on the logs. Ahead the road went down through the\
forest.\
\
\'93She won\'92t come between us, will she? The little brat.\'94\
\
\'93No. We won\'92t let her.\'94\
\
\'93How are we for money?\'94\
\
\'93We have plenty. They honored the last sight draft.\'94\
\
\'93Won\'92t your family try and get hold of you now they know you\'92re in\
Switzerland?\'94\
\
\'93Probably. I\'92ll write them something.\'94\
\
\'93Haven\'92t you written them?\'94\
\
\'93No. Only the sight draft.\'94\
\
\'93Thank God I\'92m not your family.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll send them a cable.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you care anything about them?\'94\
\
\'93I did, but we quarrelled so much it wore itself out.\'94\
\
\'93I think I\'92d like them. I\'92d probably like them very much.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s not talk about them or I\'92ll start to worry about them.\'94 After a\
while I said, \'93Let\'92s go on if you\'92re rested.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m rested.\'94\
\
We went on down the road. It was dark now and the snow squeaked under\
our boots. The night was dry and cold and very clear.\
\
\'93I love your beard,\'94 Catherine said. \'93It\'92s a great success. It looks so\
stiff and fierce and it\'92s very soft and a great pleasure.\'94\
\
\'93Do you like it better than without?\'94\
\
\'93I think so. You know, darling, I\'92m not going to cut my hair now until\
after young Catherine\'92s born. I look too big and matronly now. But after\
she\'92s born and I\'92m thin again I\'92m going to cut it and then I\'92ll be a\
