\
                              CHAPTER XLI\
\
One morning I awoke about three o\'92clock hearing Catherine stirring in\
the bed.\
\
\'93Are you all right, Cat?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve been having some pains, darling.\'94\
\
\'93Regularly?\'94\
\
\'93No, not very.\'94\
\
\'93If you have them at all regularly we\'92ll go to the hospital.\'94\
\
I was very sleepy and went back to sleep. A little while later I woke\
again.\
\
\'93Maybe you\'92d better call up the doctor,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I think maybe\
this is it.\'94\
\
I went to the phone and called the doctor. \'93How often are the pains\
coming?\'94 he asked.\
\
\'93How often are they coming, Cat?\'94\
\
\'93I should think every quarter of an hour.\'94\
\
\'93You should go to the hospital then,\'94 the doctor said. \'93I will dress and\
go there right away myself.\'94\
\
I hung up and called the garage near the station to send up a taxi. No\
one answered the phone for a long time. Then I finally got a man who\
promised to send up a taxi at once. Catherine was dressing. Her bag was\
all packed with the things she would need at the hospital and the baby\
things. Outside in the hall I rang for the elevator. There was no\
answer. I went downstairs. There was no one downstairs except the\
night-watchman. I brought the elevator up myself, put Catherine\'92s bag in\
it, she stepped in and we went down. The night-watchman opened the door\
for us and we sat outside on the stone slabs beside the stairs down to\
the driveway and waited for the taxi. The night was clear and the stars\
were out. Catherine was very excited.\
\
\'93I\'92m so glad it\'92s started,\'94 she said. \'93Now in a little while it will be\
all over.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re a good brave girl.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not afraid. I wish the taxi would come, though.\'94\
\
We heard it coming up the street and saw its headlights. It turned into\
the driveway and I helped Catherine in and the driver put the bag up in\
front.\
\
\'93Drive to the hospital,\'94 I said.\
\
We went out of the driveway and started up the hill.\
\
At the hospital we went in and I carried the bag. There was a woman at\
the desk who wrote down Catherine\'92s name, age, address, relatives and\
religion, in a book. She said she had no religion and the woman drew a\
line in the space after that word. She gave her name as Catherine Henry.\
\
\'93I will take you up to your room,\'94 she said. We went up in an elevator.\
The woman stopped it and we stepped out and followed her down a hall.\
Catherine held tight to my arm.\
\
\'93This is the room,\'94 the woman said. \'93Will you please undress and get\
into bed? Here is a nightgown for you to wear.\'94\
\
\'93I have a nightgown,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93It is better for you to wear this nightgown,\'94 the woman said.\
\
I went outside and sat on a chair in the hallway.\
\
\'93You can come in now,\'94 the woman said from the doorway. Catherine was\
lying in the narrow bed wearing a plain, square-cut nightgown that\
looked as though it were made of rough sheeting. She smiled at me.\
\
\'93I\'92m having fine pains now,\'94 she said. The woman was holding her wrist\
and timing the pains with a watch.\
\
\'93That was a big one,\'94 Catherine said. I saw it on her face.\
\
\'93Where\'92s the doctor?\'94 I asked the woman.\
\
\'93He\'92s lying down sleeping. He will be here when he is needed.\'94\
\
\'93I must do something for Madame, now,\'94 the nurse said. \'93Would you please\
step out again?\'94\
\
I went out into the hall. It was a bare hall with two windows and closed\
doors all down the corridor. It smelled of hospital. I sat on the chair\
and looked at the floor and prayed for Catherine.\
\
\'93You can come in,\'94 the nurse said. I went in.\
\
\'93Hello, darling,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
\'93How is it?\'94\
\
\'93They are coming quite often now.\'94 Her face drew up. Then she smiled.\
\
\'93That was a real one. Do you want to put your hand on my back again,\
nurse?\'94\
\
\'93If it helps you,\'94 the nurse said.\
\
\'93You go away, darling,\'94 Catherine said. \'93Go out and get something to\
eat. I may do this for a long time the nurse says.\'94\
\
\'93The first labor is usually protracted,\'94 the nurse said.\
\
\'93Please go out and get something to eat,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I\'92m fine,\
really.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll stay awhile,\'94 I said.\
\
The pains came quite regularly, then slackened off. Catherine was very\
excited. When the pains were bad she called them good ones. When they\
started to fall off she was disappointed and ashamed.\
\
\'93You go out, darling,\'94 she said. \'93I think you are just making me\
self-conscious.\'94 Her face tied up. \'93There. That was better. I so want to\
be a good wife and have this child without any foolishness. Please go\
and get some breakfast, darling, and then come back. I won\'92t miss you.\
Nurse is splendid to me.\'94\
\
\'93You have plenty of time for breakfast,\'94 the nurse said.\
\
\'93I\'92ll go then. Good-by, sweet.\'94\
\
\'93Good-by,\'94 Catherine said, \'93and have a fine breakfast for me too.\'94\
\
\'93Where can I get breakfast?\'94 I asked the nurse.\
\
\'93There\'92s a caf\'e9 down the street at the square,\'94 she said. \'93It should be\
open now.\'94\
\
Outside it was getting light. I walked down the empty street to the\
caf\'e9. There was a light in the window. I went in and stood at the zinc\
bar and an old man served me a glass of white wine and a brioche. The\
brioche was yesterday\'92s. I dipped it in the wine and then drank a glass\
of coffee.\
\
\'93What do you do at this hour?\'94 the old man asked.\
\
\'93My wife is in labor at the hospital.\'94\
\
\'93So. I wish you good luck.\'94\
\
\'93Give me another glass of wine.\'94\
\
He poured it from the bottle slopping it over a little so some ran down\
on the zinc. I drank this glass, paid and went out. Outside along the\
street were the refuse cans from the houses waiting for the collector. A\
dog was nosing at one of the cans.\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94 I asked and looked in the can to see if there was\
anything I could pull out for him; there was nothing on top but\
coffee-grounds, dust and some dead flowers.\
\
\'93There isn\'92t anything, dog,\'94 I said. The dog crossed the street. I went\
up the stairs in the hospital to the floor Catherine was on and down the\
hall to her room. I knocked on the door. There was no answer. I opened\
the door; the room was empty, except for Catherine\'92s bag on a chair and\
her dressing-gown hanging on a hook on the wall. I went out and down the\
hall, looking for somebody. I found a nurse.\
\
\'93Where is Madame Henry?\'94\
\
\'93A lady has just gone to the delivery room.\'94\
\
\'93Where is it?\'94\
\
\'93I will show you.\'94\
\
She took me down to the end of the hall. The door of the room was partly\
open. I could see Catherine lying on a table, covered by a sheet. The\
nurse was on one side and the doctor stood on the other side of the\
table beside some cylinders. The doctor held a rubber mask attached to a\
tube in one hand.\
\
\'93I will give you a gown and you can go in,\'94 the nurse said. \'93Come in\
here, please.\'94\
\
She put a white gown on me and pinned it at the neck in back with a\
safety pin.\
\
\'93Now you can go in,\'94 she said. I went into the room.\
\
\'93Hello, darling,\'94 Catherine said in a strained voice. \'93I\'92m not doing\
much.\'94\
\
\'93You are Mr. Henry?\'94 the doctor asked.\
\
\'93Yes. How is everything going, doctor?\'94\
\
\'93Things are going very well,\'94 the doctor said. \'93We came in here where it\
is easy to give gas for the pains.\'94\
\
\'93I want it now,\'94 Catherine said. The doctor placed the rubber mask over\
her face and turned a dial and I watched Catherine breathing deeply and\
