\
\'93It wasn\'92t much,\'94 Catherine said. She smiled. \'93I\'92m a fool about the gas.\
It\'92s wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll get some for the home,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93_There one comes_,\'94 Catherine said quickly. The doctor turned the dial\
and looked at his watch.\
\
\'93What is the interval now?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93About a minute.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you want lunch?\'94\
\
\'93I will have something pretty soon,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93You must have something to eat, doctor,\'94 Catherine said. \'93I\'92m so sorry\
I go on so long. Couldn\'92t my husband give me the gas?\'94\
\
\'93If you wish,\'94 the doctor said. \'93You turn it to the numeral two.\'94\
\
\'93I see,\'94 I said. There was a marker on a dial that turned with a handle.\
\
\'93_I want it now_,\'94 Catherine said. She held the mask tight to her face.\
I turned the dial to number two and when Catherine put down the mask I\
turned it off. It was very good of the doctor to let me do something.\
\
\'93Did you do it, darling?\'94 Catherine asked. She stroked my wrist.\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re so lovely.\'94 She was a little drunk from the gas.\
\
\'93I will eat from a tray in the next room,\'94 the doctor said. \'93You can\
call me any moment.\'94 While the time passed I watched him eat, then,\
after a while, I saw that he was lying down and smoking a cigarette.\
Catherine was getting very tired.\
\
\'93Do you think I\'92ll ever have this baby?\'94 she asked.\
\
\'93Yes, of course you will.\'94\
\
\'93I try as hard as I can. I push down but it goes away. _There it comes.\
Give it to me._\'94\
\
At two o\'92clock I went out and had lunch. There were a few men in the\
caf\'e9 sitting with coffee and glasses of kirsch or marc on the tables. I\
sat down at a table. \'93Can I eat?\'94 I asked the waiter.\
\
\'93It is past time for lunch.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t there anything for all hours?\'94\
\
\'93You can have _choucroute_.\'94\
\
\'93Give me _choucroute_ and beer.\'94\
\
\'93A demi or a bock?\'94\
\
\'93A light demi.\'94\
\
The waiter brought a dish of sauerkraut with a slice of ham over the top\
and a sausage buried in the hot wine-soaked cabbage. I ate it and drank\
the beer. I was very hungry. I watched the people at the tables in the\
caf\'e9. At one table they were playing cards. Two men at the table next me\
were talking and smoking. The caf\'e9 was full of smoke. The zinc bar,\
where I had breakfasted, had three people behind it now; the old man, a\
plump woman in a black dress who sat behind a counter and kept track of\
everything served to the tables, and a boy in an apron. I wondered how\
many children the woman had and what it had been like.\
\
When I was through with the _choucroute_ I went back to the hospital.\
The street was all clean now. There were no refuse cans out. The day was\
cloudy but the sun was trying to come through. I rode upstairs in the\
elevator, stepped out and went down the hall to Catherine\'92s room, where\
I had left my white gown. I put it on and pinned it in back at the neck.\
I looked in the glass and saw myself looking like a fake doctor with a\
beard. I went down the hall to the delivery room. The door was closed\
and I knocked. No one answered so I turned the handle and went in. The\
doctor sat by Catherine. The nurse was doing something at the other end\
of the room.\
\
\'93Here is your husband,\'94 the doctor said.\
\
\'93Oh, darling, I have the most wonderful doctor,\'94 Catherine said in a\
very strange voice. \'93He\'92s been telling me the most wonderful story and\
when the pain came too badly he put me all the way out. He\'92s wonderful.\
You\'92re wonderful, doctor.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re drunk,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I know it,\'94 Catherine said. \'93But you shouldn\'92t say it.\'94 Then \'93_Give it\
to me. Give it to me._\'94 She clutched hold of the mask and breathed short\
and deep, pantingly, making the respirator click. Then she gave a long\
sigh and the doctor reached with his left hand and lifted away the mask.\
\
\'93That was a very big one,\'94 Catherine said. Her voice was very strange.\
\'93I\'92m not going to die now, darling. I\'92m past where I was going to die.\
Aren\'92t you glad?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you get in that place again.\'94\
\
\'93I won\'92t. I\'92m not afraid of it though. I won\'92t die, darling.\'94\
\
\'93You will not do any such foolishness,\'94 the doctor said. \'93You would not\
die and leave your husband.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, no. I won\'92t die. I wouldn\'92t die. It\'92s silly to die. There it comes.\
_Give it to me._\'94\
\
After a while the doctor said, \'93You will go out, Mr. Henry, for a few\
moments and I will make an examination.\'94\
\
\'93He wants to see how I am doing,\'94 Catherine said. \'93You can come back\
afterward, darling, can\'92t he, doctor?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 said the doctor. \'93I will send word when he can come back.\'94\
\
I went out the door and down the hall to the room where Catherine was to\
be after the baby came. I sat in a chair there and looked at the room. I\
had the paper in my coat that I had bought when I went out for lunch and\
I read it. It was beginning to be dark outside and I turned the light on\
to read. After a while I stopped reading and turned off the light and\
watched it get dark outside. I wondered why the doctor did not send for\
me. Maybe it was better I was away. He probably wanted me away for a\
while. I looked at my watch. If he did not send for me in ten minutes I\
would go down anyway.\
\
Poor, poor dear Cat. And this was the price you paid for sleeping\
together. This was the end of the trap. This was what people got for\
loving each other. Thank God for gas, anyway. What must it have been\
like before there were an\'e6sthetics? Once it started, they were in the\
mill-race. Catherine had a good time in the time of pregnancy. It wasn\'92t\
bad. She was hardly ever sick. She was not awfully uncomfortable until\
toward the last. So now they got her in the end. You never got away with\
anything. Get away hell! It would have been the same if we had been\
married fifty times. And what if she should die? She won\'92t die. People\
don\'92t die in childbirth nowadays. That was what all husbands thought.\
Yes, but what if she should die? She won\'92t die. She\'92s just having a bad\
time. The initial labor is usually protracted. She\'92s only having a bad\
time. Afterward we\'92d say what a bad time and Catherine would say it\
wasn\'92t really so bad. But what if she should die? She can\'92t die. Yes,\
but what if she should die? She can\'92t, I tell you. Don\'92t be a fool. It\'92s\
just a bad time. It\'92s just nature giving her hell. It\'92s only the first\
labor, which is almost always protracted. Yes, but what if she should\
die? She can\'92t die. Why would she die? What reason is there for her to\
die? There\'92s just a child that has to be born, the by-product of good\
nights in Milan. It makes trouble and is born and then you look after it\
and get fond of it maybe. But what if she should die? She won\'92t die. But\
what if she should die? She won\'92t. She\'92s all right. But what if she\
should die? She can\'92t die. But what if she should die? Hey, what about\
that? What if she should die?\
\
The doctor came into the room.\
\
\'93How does it go, doctor?\'94\
\
\'93It doesn\'92t go,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93What do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93Just that. I made an examination\'97\'94 He detailed the result of the\
examination. \'93Since then I\'92ve waited to see. But it doesn\'92t go.\'94\
\
\'93What do you advise?\'94\
\
\'93There are two things. Either a high forceps delivery which can tear and\
be quite dangerous besides being possibly bad for the child, and a\
C\'e6sarean.\'94\
\
\'93What is the danger of a C\'e6sarean?\'94 What if she should die!\
\
\'93It should be no greater than the danger of an ordinary delivery.\'94\
\
\'93Would you do it yourself?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. I would need possibly an hour to get things ready and to get the\
people I would need. Perhaps a little less.\'94\
\
\'93What do you think?\'94\
\
\'93I would advise a C\'e6sarean operation. If it were my wife I would do a\
C\'e6sarean.\'94\
\
\'93What are the after effects?\'94\
\
\'93There are none. There is only the scar.\'94\
\
\'93What about infection?\'94\
\
\'93The danger is not so great as in a high forceps delivery.\'94\
\
\'93What if you just went on and did nothing?\'94\
\
\'93You would have to do something eventually. Mrs. Henry is already losing\
much of her strength. The sooner we operate now the safer.\'94\
\
\'93Operate as soon as you can,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I will go and give the instructions.\'94\
\
I went into the delivery room. The nurse was with Catherine who lay on\
the table, big under the sheet, looking very pale and tired.\
\
\'93Did you tell him he could do it?\'94 she asked.\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t that grand. Now it will be all over in an hour. I\'92m almost done,\
darling. I\'92m going all to pieces. _Please give me that._ It doesn\'92t\
work. _Oh, it doesn\'92t work!_\'94\
\
\'93Breathe deeply.\'94\
\
\'93I am. Oh, it doesn\'92t work any more. It doesn\'92t work!\'94\
\
\'93Get another cylinder,\'94 I said to the nurse.\
\
\'93That is a new cylinder.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m just a fool, darling,\'94 Catherine said. \'93But it doesn\'92t work any\
more.\'94 She began to cry. \'93Oh, I wanted so to have this baby and not make\
trouble, and now I\'92m all done and all gone to pieces and it doesn\'92t\
work. Oh, darling, it doesn\'92t work at all. I don\'92t care if I die if it\
will only stop. Oh, please, darling, please make it stop. _There it\
comes. Oh Oh Oh!_\'94 She breathed sobbingly in the mask. \'93It doesn\'92t work.\
It doesn\'92t work. It doesn\'92t work. Don\'92t mind me, darling. Please don\'92t\
cry. Don\'92t mind me. I\'92m just gone all to pieces. You poor sweet. I love\
you so and I\'92ll be good again. I\'92ll be good this time. _Can\'92t they give\
me something?_ If they could only give me something.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll make it work. I\'92ll turn it all the way.\'94\
\
\'93Give it to me now.\'94\
\
I turned the dial all the way and as she breathed hard and deep her hand\
relaxed on the mask. I shut off the gas and lifted the mask. She came\
back from a long way away.\
\
\'93That was lovely, darling. Oh, you\'92re so good to me.\
\
\'93You be brave, because I can\'92t do that all the time. It might kill you.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not brave any more, darling. I\'92m all broken. They\'92ve broken me. I\
know it now.\'94\
\
\'93Everybody is that way.\'94\
\
\'93But it\'92s awful. They just keep it up till they break you.\'94\
\
\'93In an hour it will be over.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t that lovely? Darling, I won\'92t die, will I?\'94\
\
\'93No. I promise you won\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Because I don\'92t want to die and leave you, but I get so tired of it and\
I feel I\'92m going to die.\'94\
\
\'93Nonsense. Everybody feels that.\'94\
\
\'93Sometimes I know I\'92m going to die.\'94\
\
\'93You won\'92t. You can\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93But what if I should?\'94\
\
\'93I won\'92t let you.\'94\
\
\'93Give it to me quick. _Give it to me!_\'94\
\
Then afterward, \'93I won\'92t die. I won\'92t let myself die.\'94\
\
\'93Of course you won\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll stay with me?\'94\
\
\'93Not to watch it.\'94\
\
\'93No, just to be there.\'94\
\
\'93Sure. I\'92ll be there all the time.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re so good to me. There, give it to me. Give me some more. _It\'92s\
not working!_\'94\
\
I turned the dial to three and then four. I wished the doctor would come\
back. I was afraid of the numbers above two.\
\
\
\
Finally a new doctor came in with two nurses and they lifted Catherine\
onto a wheeled stretcher and we started down the hall. The stretcher\
went rapidly down the hall and into the elevator where every one had to\
crowd against the wall to make room; then up, then an open door and out\
of the elevator and down the hall on rubber wheels to the operating\
room. I did not recognize the doctor with his cap and mask on. There was\
another doctor and more nurses.\
\
\'93_They\'92ve got to give me something_,\'94 Catherine said. \'93_They\'92ve got to\
give me something._ Oh please, doctor, give me enough to do some good!\'94\
\
One of the doctors put a mask over her face and I looked through the\
door and saw the bright small amphitheatre of the operating room.\
\
\'93You can go in the other door and sit up there,\'94 a nurse said to me.\
There were benches behind a rail that looked down on the white table and\
the lights. I looked at Catherine. The mask was over her face and she\
was quiet now. They wheeled the stretcher forward. I turned away and\
walked down the hall. Two nurses were hurrying toward the entrance to\
the gallery.\
\
\'93It\'92s a C\'e6sarean,\'94 one said. \'93They\'92re going to do a C\'e6sarean.\'94\
\
The other one laughed, \'93We\'92re just in time. Aren\'92t we lucky?\'94 They went\
in the door that led to the gallery.\
\
Another nurse came along. She was hurrying too.\
\
\'93You go right in there. Go right in,\'94 she said.\
\
\'93I\'92m staying outside.\'94\
\
She hurried in. I walked up and down the hall. I was afraid to go in. I\
looked out the window. It was dark but in the light from the window I\
could see it was raining. I went into a room at the far end of the hall\
and looked at the labels on bottles in a glass case. Then I came out and\
stood in the empty hall and watched the door of the operating room.\
\
A doctor came out followed by a nurse. He held something in his two\
hands that looked like a freshly skinned rabbit and hurried across the\
corridor with it and in through another door. I went down to the door he\
had gone into and found them in the room doing things to a new-born\
child. The doctor held him up for me to see. He held him by the heels\
and slapped him.\
\
\'93Is he all right?\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s magnificent. He\'92ll weigh five kilos.\'94\
\
I had no feeling for him. He did not seem to have anything to do with\
me. I felt no feeling of fatherhood.\
\
\'93Aren\'92t you proud of your son?\'94 the nurse asked. They were washing him\
and wrapping him in something. I saw the little dark face and dark hand,\
but I did not see him move or hear him cry. The doctor was doing\
something to him again. He looked upset.\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93He nearly killed his mother.\'94\
\
\'93It isn\'92t the little darling\'92s fault. Didn\'92t you want a boy?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. The doctor was busy with him. He held him up by the feet\
and slapped him. I did not wait to see it. I went out in the hall. I\
could go in now and see. I went in the door and a little way down the\
gallery. The nurses who were sitting at the rail motioned for me to come\
down where they were. I shook my head. I could see enough where I was.\
\
I thought Catherine was dead. She looked dead. Her face was gray, the\
part of it that I could see. Down below, under the light, the doctor was\
sewing up the great long, forcep-spread, thick-edged, wound. Another\
doctor in a mask gave the an\'e6sthetic. Two nurses in masks handed things.\
It looked like a drawing of the Inquisition. I knew as I watched I could\
have watched it all, but I was glad I hadn\'92t. I do not think I could\
have watched them cut, but I watched the wound closed into a high welted\
ridge with quick skilful-looking stitches like a cobbler\'92s, and was\
glad. When the wound was closed I went out into the hall and walked up\
and down again. After a while the doctor came out.\
\
\'93How is she?\'94\
\
\'93She is all right. Did you watch?\'94\
\
He looked tired.\
\
\'93I saw you sew up. The incision looked very long.\'94\
\
\'93You thought so?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Will that scar flatten out?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes.\'94\
\
After a while they brought out the wheeled stretcher and took it very\
rapidly down the hallway to the elevator. I went along beside it.\
Catherine was moaning. Downstairs they put her in the bed in her room. I\
sat in a chair at the foot of the bed. There was a nurse in the room. I\
got up and stood by the bed. It was dark in the room. Catherine put out\
her hand, \'93Hello, darling,\'94 she said. Her voice was very weak and tired.\
\
\'93Hello, you sweet.\'94\
\
\'93What sort of baby was it?\'94\
\
\'93Sh\'97don\'92t talk,\'94 the nurse said.\
\
\'93A boy. He\'92s long and wide and dark.\'94\
\
\'93Is he all right?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s fine.\'94\
\
I saw the nurse look at me strangely.\
\
\'93I\'92m awfully tired,\'94 Catherine said. \'93And I hurt like hell. Are you all\
right, darling?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m fine. Don\'92t talk.\'94\
\
\'93You were lovely to me. Oh, darling, I hurt dreadfully. What does he\
look like?\'94\
\
\'93He looks like a skinned rabbit with a puckered-up old-man\'92s face.\'94\
\
\'93You must go out,\'94 the nurse said. \'93Madame Henry must not talk.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll be outside,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93Go and get something to eat.\'94\
\
\'93No. I\'92ll be outside.\'94 I kissed Catherine. She was very gray and weak\
and tired.\
\
\'93May I speak to you?\'94 I said to the nurse. She came out in the hall with\
me. I walked a little way down the hall.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with the baby?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93Didn\'92t you know?\'94\
\
\'93No.\'94\
\
\'93He wasn\'92t alive.\'94\
\
\'93He was dead?\'94\
\
\'93They couldn\'92t start him breathing. The cord was caught around his neck\
or something.\'94\
\
\'93So he\'92s dead.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. It\'92s such a shame. He was such a fine big boy. I thought you\
knew.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I said. \'93You better go back in with Madame.\'94\
\
I sat down on the chair in front of a table where there were nurses\'92\
reports hung on clips at the side and looked out of the window. I could\
see nothing but the dark and the rain falling across the light from the\
window. So that was it. The baby was dead. That was why the doctor\
looked so tired. But why had they acted the way they did in the room\
with him? They supposed he would come around and start breathing\
probably. I had no religion but I knew he ought to have been baptized.\
But what if he never breathed at all. He hadn\'92t. He had never been\
alive. Except in Catherine. I\'92d felt him kick there often enough. But I\
hadn\'92t for a week. Maybe he was choked all the time. Poor little kid. I\
wished the hell I\'92d been choked like that. No I didn\'92t. Still there\
would not be all this dying to go through. Now Catherine would die. That\
was what you did. You died. You did not know what it was about. You\
never had time to learn. They threw you in and told you the rules and\
the first time they caught you off base they killed you. Or they killed\
you gratuitously like Aymo. Or gave you the syphilis like Rinaldo. But\
they killed you in the end. You could count on that. Stay around and\
they would kill you.\
\
Once in camp I put a log on top of the fire and it was full of ants. As\
it commenced to burn, the ants swarmed out and went first toward the\
centre where the fire was; then turned back and ran toward the end. When\
there were enough on the end they fell off into the fire. Some got out,\
their bodies burnt and flattened, and went off not knowing where they\
were going. But most of them went toward the fire and then back toward\
the end and swarmed on the cool end and finally fell off into the fire.\
I remember thinking at the time that it was the end of the world and a\
splendid chance to be a messiah and lift the log off the fire and throw\
it out where the ants could get off onto the ground. But I did not do\
anything but throw a tin cup of water on the log, so that I would have\
the cup empty to put whiskey in before I added water to it. I think the\
cup of water on the burning log only steamed the ants.\
\
So now I sat out in the hall and waited to hear how Catherine was. The\
nurse did not come out, so after a while I went to the door and opened\
it very softly and looked in. I could not see at first because there was\
a bright light in the hall and it was dark in the room. Then I saw the\
nurse sitting by the bed and Catherine\'92s head on a pillow, and she all\
flat under the sheet. The nurse put her finger to her lips, then stood\
up and came to the door.\
\
\'93How is she?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93She\'92s all right,\'94 the nurse said. \'93You should go and have your supper\
and then come back if you wish.\'94\
\
I went down the hall and then down the stairs and out the door of the\
hospital and down the dark street in the rain to the caf\'e9. It was\
brightly lighted inside and there were many people at the tables. I did\
not see a place to sit, and a waiter came up to me and took my wet coat\
and hat and showed me a place at a table across from an elderly man who\
was drinking beer and reading the evening paper. I sat down and asked\
the waiter what the _plat du jour_ was.\
\
\'93Veal stew\'97but it is finished.\'94\
\
\'93What can I have to eat?\'94\
\
\'93Ham and eggs, eggs with cheese, or _choucroute_.\'94\
\
\'93I had _choucroute_ this noon,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93That\'92s true,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s true. You ate _choucroute_ this noon.\'94\
He was a middle-aged man with a bald top to his head and his hair\
slicked over it. He had a kind face.\
\
\'93What do you want? Ham and eggs or eggs with cheese?\'94\
\
\'93Ham and eggs,\'94 I said, \'93and beer.\'94\
\
\'93A demi-blonde?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I remembered,\'94 he said. \'93You took a demi-blonde this noon.\'94\
\
I ate the ham and eggs and drank the beer. The ham and eggs were in a\
round dish\'97the ham underneath and the eggs on top. It was very hot and\
at the first mouthful I had to take a drink of beer to cool my mouth. I\
was hungry and I asked the waiter for another order. I drank several\
glasses of beer. I was not thinking at all but read the paper of the man\
opposite me. It was about the break through on the British front. When\
he realized I was reading the back of his paper he folded it over. I\
thought of asking the waiter for a paper, but I could not concentrate.\
It was hot in the caf\'e9 and the air was bad. Many of the people at the\
tables knew one another. There were several card games going on. The\
waiters were busy bringing drinks from the bar to the tables. Two men\
came in and could find no place to sit. They stood opposite the table\
where I was. I ordered another beer. I was not ready to leave yet. It\
was too soon to go back to the hospital. I tried not to think and to be\
perfectly calm. The men stood around but no one was leaving, so they\
went out. I drank another beer. There was quite a pile of saucers now on\
the table in front of me. The man opposite me had taken off his\
spectacles, put them away in a case, folded his paper and put it in his\
pocket and now sat holding his liqueur glass and looking out at the\
room. Suddenly I knew I had to get back. I called the waiter, paid the\
reckoning, got into my coat, put on my hat and started out the door. I\
walked through the rain up to the hospital.\
\
Upstairs I met the nurse coming down the hall.\
\
\'93I just called you at the hotel,\'94 she said. Something dropped inside me.\
\
\'93What is wrong?\'94\
\
\'93Mrs. Henry has had a hemorrhage.\'94\
\
\'93Can I go in?\'94\
\
\'93No, not yet. The doctor is with her.\'94\
\
\'93Is it dangerous?\'94\
\
\'93It is very dangerous.\'94 The nurse went into the room and shut the door.\
I sat outside in the hall. Everything was gone inside of me. I did not\
think. I could not think. I knew she was going to die and I prayed that\
she would not. Don\'92t let her die. Oh, God, please don\'92t let her die.\
I\'92ll do anything for you if you won\'92t let her die. Please, please,\
please, dear God, don\'92t let her die. Dear God, don\'92t let her die.\
Please, please, please don\'92t let her die. God please make her not die.\
I\'92ll do anything you say if you don\'92t let her die. You took the baby but\
don\'92t let her die. That was all right but don\'92t let her die. Please,\
please, dear God, don\'92t let her die.\
\
The nurse opened the door and motioned with her finger for me to come. I\
followed her into the room. Catherine did not look up when I came in. I\
went over to the side of the bed. The doctor was standing by the bed on\
the opposite side. Catherine looked at me and smiled. I bent down over\
the bed and started to cry.\
\
\'93Poor darling,\'94 Catherine said very softly. She looked gray.\
\
\'93You\'92re all right, Cat,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92re going to be all right.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to die,\'94 she said; then waited and said, \'93I hate it.\'94\
\
I took her hand.\
\
\'93Don\'92t touch me,\'94 she said. I let go of her hand. She smiled. \'93Poor\
darling. You touch me all you want.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll be all right, Cat. I know you\'92ll be all right.\'94\
\
\'93I meant to write you a letter to have if anything happened, but I\
didn\'92t do it.\'94\
\
\'93Do you want me to get a priest or any one to come and see you?\'94\
\
\'93Just you,\'94 she said. Then a little later, \'93I\'92m not afraid. I just hate\
it.\'94\
\
\'93You must not talk so much,\'94 the doctor said.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 Catherine said.\
\
